<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / South African talks resume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICAN groups from across the political spectrum yesterday formally
resumed constitutional talks suspended since last May, but avoided
addressing any of the substantive issues blocking agreement on a
post-apartheid constitution.
The talks, which had been planned as a two-day session, ended after only one
day following agreement between the 26 parties to defer consideration of all
important issues - including the name of the forum, participation in
negotiations, as well as whether South Africa should be a federal or unitary
state - to a smaller 'negotiation council' due to meet on April 15.
Yesterday's meeting agreed certain procedural issues, such as how decisions
would be taken in future meetings. It was agreed that 'sufficient consensus'
would be required to take decisions. This means that participating parties
can be overruled if their opposition does not halt all progress in the
talks.
But all of the tough work of negotiation remains to be done.
Parties must agree on a bilateral proposal from the African National
Congress and the government for multi-party power-sharing, and the vexed
issue of the form of the state - federal or unitary - remains unresolved.
The parties discussed the issue of violence, which had been expected to
prove an obstacle to talks, without the kind of virulent verbal attacks
which had been expected.
However, the ruling National Party questioned the sincerity of one
conference participant, the Pan Africanist Congress, whose armed wing has
been accused of involvement in a number of recent murders of whites.
</TEXT>
