<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / IG Metall says 100,000 strike over pay in east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of workers in eastern Germany yesterday took to the streets to
protest against the decision by steel and engineering employers not to pay
agreed increases aimed at bringing wages in the east up to western levels by
April 1994.
IG Metall, Germany's largest union, said that about 100,000 workers had
walked out, with stoppages reported in more than 220 factories in the states
of Brandenburg, Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia, as well as east Berlin.
The union is hoping the wages row will help mobilise eastern German workers
on other issues.
IG Metall, which is losing members across Germany, also wants to show it
still has political muscle.
'We have to show the employers that we will not allow them to break this
contract reached in March 1991,' said Mr Michael Bohm, spokesman for IG
Metall in Berlin. 'The employers are determined to break the tradition of
collective wage bargaining.'
The union is also concerned about living standards in the east. Easterners
pay western German prices, while wages in the region are 70 per cent of
levels in the west. This is why the union is still demanding the increases
agreed in 1991 - a 26 per cent pay increase for engineering workers and a 21
per cent rise for the steel sector. However, such pay increases do not
reflect productivity, which, on average, is 70 per cent below western German
levels. Economists fear that high labour costs in eastern Germany will drive
away investors, increase unemployment - already 18 per cent but about double
that counting those on jobless schemes - and severely undermine any hopes of
an economic upturn in the east.
A renewed round of talks last month broke off after employers tried to
negotiate for 9 per cent wage increases, which is about equivalent to
eastern Germany's expected inflation rate this year.
'Our answer is simple. Since our members are going to lose their jobs, we
might as well fight for these large pay rises so that they can have higher
unemployment benefit once they are out of work,' said Mr Bohm.
It is not certain eastern German workers feel the same: many have said they
would accept low wages in the short term, much as workers in the west are
doing, in return for jobs and investment. Both sides, and former communist
managers who were party to the wage equality contract in 1991, would
probably concede the agreement was flawed. For political reasons eastern
managers wanted high wages and the western employers were worried that lower
wages in the east would make eastern Germany more competitive. The unions
felt that higher wages in the east would help to keep wages high in western
Germany.
The economic circumstances in eastern Germany were different in 1991 too,
when it still had markets in the Soviet Union. The markets are no longer
there.
</TEXT>
