<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Naples probe turns to judges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Naples investigation into links between politicians, businessmen and
members of the Camorra, the local mafia, yesterday extended to embrace the
judiciary.
Two senior judges were yesterday served notice that they were under
investigation for collusion with the Camorra, while there was speculation
that a further five judges were also involved.
It is the first time such a direct accusation has been made against the
Naples judiciary, despite the long nurtured suspicion that an essential link
in the protection of the city's extensive network of organised crime was
cover from the courts.
In the past week, Palermo magistrates have also revealed they have sent
dossiers on one of Italy's best-known appeal court judges, Mr Corrado
Carnevale, to Rome. Mr Carnevale, dubbed 'the sentence killer', has presided
over a number of appeals of prominent mafiosi and found technical arguments
to reduce their sentences. New accusations may also be on the way about
Christian Democrat activities in Sicily after police seized party documents
on Wednesday.
The involvement of the judiciary in the corruption scandals threatens to
pose delicate problems. It is often the younger investigate magistrates who
are digging up evidence while the judges hearing cases in court have taken a
very restrictive view of evidence and proof, causing 75 per cent of all
prosecutions to fail.
The two judges named yesterday were Mr Armando Cono Lancuba, prosecutor
general at Melfi, 100km from Naples, who for a long time operated in the
city's courts, and Mr Alberto Lamberti, already under disciplinary
proceedings and the subject of an assassination attempt in 1982. They are
understood to have been named by Mr Pasquale Galasso, a former Camorra boss,
who is now co-operating with the authorities under a plea bargaining
programme. Mr Galasso, who looked after the business interests - valued at
L1,500bn (Pounds 684m) - of the Camorra head, Mr Carmine Alfieri, has
provided the authorities with the names of dozens of businessmen and
politicians linked to organised crime.
His confessions, combined with those of a Christian Democrat deputy, have
enabled the police to uncover the city's extensive corruption network in
under two months.
On one day alone the Naples police served 115 arrest warrants.
The significance of developments in Naples is that only here did the
Christian Democrats and Socialists hang on to their votes in the elections
of April last year.
This has been the stronghold of patronage politics.
</TEXT>
<XX>
