<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Vance's peace role offered to Norwegian
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Thorvald Stoltenberg, the Norwegian foreign minister, is expected to take
over from Mr Cyrus Vance, the veteran former US secretary of state, as one
of the two international peace negotiators on the former Yugoslavia, though
he has yet to make a final decision whether to accept the post.
It has come as no surprise that Mr Vance, 76, is stepping down. He made it
clear at the beginning of the year that he would soon give up the arduous
task of mediator, which has required constant travel between Geneva, New
York and the former Yugoslavia and the chairing of lengthy negotiating
sessions.
Though robust in appearance, Mr Vance has been troubled by ill health and
has frequently said that he wanted to devote more time to his New York law
practice and his family. Most observers, however, expected him to wait until
a peace agreement in Bosnia was signed and sealed. That could still happen,
since Mr Stoltenberg is not due to take over from him until next month.
If he accepts the appointment, following consultations with his prime
minister, Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, he will be joining Lord David Owen, the
European Community's representative on the two-man mediators' team. The
61-year-old Mr Stoltenberg has been offered the job as co-chairman of the
conference on the former Yugoslavia by Mr Boutros Boutros-Ghali, the United
Nations secretary-general.
A Balkans expert, Mr Stoltenberg worked as a diplomat in Belgrade from 1961
to 1964, speaks Serbo-Croat and briefly held the posts of Norway's UN
representative and UN High Commissioner for Refugees.
A Norwegian foreign ministry spokesman said that Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali
had the backing of the five permanent members of the security council in
offering Mr Stoltenberg the post.
Though Mr Stoltenberg, coming from a small country, is not widely known as
an international statesman, the UN secretary-general clearly considers that
his considerable experience of Yugoslav problems and his familiarity with
the UN are good qualifications for the job.
Mr Vance, who has long had a close working and personal friendship with Lord
Owen, began his association with the UN at the end of 1989 and was appointed
the UN's special envoy to Yugoslavia in 1991. One of his main achievements
was to have negotiated a ceasefire in January 1992 ending six months of
bitter fighting between Croats and Serbs living in the newly created
republic of Croatia.
Subsequently, he represented the UN on fact-finding missions to South Africa
and inquiries into the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute between Azerbaijan and
Armenia before being appointed co-chairman of the conference on the former
Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
