<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Death of royal who nurtured democracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DON Juan de Borbon, Count of Barcelona and father of King Juan Carlos, died
in hospital in Pamplona aged 79 yesterday. Don Juan is to be buried with the
full funeral honours accorded to a reigning monarch, although he never was
one, reflecting the vital role that Don Juan played in identifying the
monarchy with the return of democracy to Spain.
It was largely because of Don Juan's lifelong defence of political pluralism
that his son, Don Juan Carlos, was able to credibly project himself after
General Franco's death as a constitutional king.
Son of King Alfonso XIII and Queen Ena of Battemberg, a grand-daughter of
Queen Victoria, Don Juan left Spain with the royal family when a republic
was proclaimed in 1931.
In 1945 Don Juan issued a manifesto calling on General Franco to step down
and setting an agenda for restoration of the monarchy and free elections.
His stand earned him the enmity of Franco who jumped the line of royal
succession and chose Don Juan Carlos, who had been educated in Spain, to
succeed him.
The tables were turned following Franco's death in 1975 when Don Juan Carlos
turned out to be his father's heir rather than the dictator's. In May 1977,
a month before the first post-Franco general elections, Don Juan moved back
to Spain and renounced his right to the throne.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
