<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News in Brief: Suchard takes Dollars
5m Polish stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JACOBS SUCHARD, the Swiss confectionery group owned by Philip Morris, has
agreed to pay Dollars 5m for an 80 per cent share in the Olza factory, a
chocolate wafer producer in southern Poland, writes Christopher Bobinski in
Warsaw.
The agreement, signed yesterday, includes a commitment for immediate
investments in the plant worth Dollars 11.3m and to spend a further Dollars
15m at a later date.
Olza's had sales last year of Dollars 24m, of which 15 per cent was
exported. The purchase is Jacobs Suchard's first investment in Poland after
it had a factory it owned in Krakow nationalised in the 1940s.
The company has, however, been marketing its coffee and chocolate products
there for the past two years. The disposal comes as a question mark
continues to hang over Philip Morris's efforts to purchase the Krakow
tobacco factory in a deal which could be worth in excess of Dollars 400m.
Philip Morris has had its Marlboro cigarettes made in Krakow under a
co-operation agreement since the early 1970s. Recently, the Sejm, (upper
house of parliament) passed a resolution calling on the government to
maintain a state monopoly in the tobacco and alcohol sectors. However, the
privatisation ministry is still hoping to get the resolution reinterpreted
to allow the purchase to go ahead.
</TEXT>
