<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Televised debates to go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC AMBASSADORS yesterday voted unanimously to accept television cameras into
three EC ministerial debates next Monday and Tuesday in Luxembourg.
Their vote follows the vetoing of three requests earlier this month by the
current Danish presidency of the EC, for the broadcast of debates on global
warming, transport policy, and the common fisheries policy. Belgium,
Luxembourg and Portugal were the main objectors.
Monday's and Tuesday's televised debates will cover the opening of
negotiations on Norway's entry to the EC; how to make the internal market
work, and the role of trade unions and employers in shaping a strategy to
create jobs.
Denmark is fighting hard to demonstrate to its own people that the EC is
opening up its secretive decision-making to public scrutiny, in a bid to
sway Danes who voted against Maastricht last June to endorse it in a second
referendum due on May 18.
The Commission also distanced itself from a public relations report,
commissioned after the Edinburgh summit and published yesterday, which calls
for the centralisation of EC information policy.
