<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (21): Analysts urge more liberalisation -
Paul Adams assesses progress and setbacks in the agricultural sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SINCE 1986 the structural adjustment programme (SAP) has started to provide
practical help and better prices to the small-scale farmers who make up most
of the rural population and account for 90 per cent of agricultural
production.
Devaluation of the naira has strengthened exports and reduced the
competitiveness of certain imports, while progress has been made in the
production of staple and cash crops. Parastatals no longer control the
marketing of farm output.
Nigeria remains, however, a large net importer of food, according to the
latest official figures. Imports in 1990 cost nearly Dollars 436m while
exports during 1990/91 season earned N2.28bn.
More seriously for the farmer, SAP has not prevented costs overtaking
revenues. A study by a Nigerian consultancy shows that agricultural input
costs have risen faster than output prices. Devaluation has been a mixed
blessing for local farmers, while inflation has pushed up interest rates.
Most analysts warn that agricultural growth will fail to outpace population
expansion unless the process of deregulation is completed, funding is
improved and government policies plan for long-term development. The
production gains of the past five years may have been achieved at the cost
of nutrient depletion, soil erosion and deforestation.
Concerns about agricultural policy focus on four main issues:
Too many programmes. The main thrust of SAP has been to nurture small-scale
traditional farming, based on low input costs and high employment. Yet
Nigeria is also pursuing big projects to import machinery. It is also
building large dams which damage the balance of payments, accelerate
environmental problems and are, in any case, geared primarily to
large-scale, sophisticated farming and food processing.
The World Bank has devoted about Dollars 650m - a third of its lending in
Nigeria - to the agricultural sector in order to promote gradual,
small-scale improvements. The principal method has been to fund
decentralised agricultural development programmes (ADPs), which are due to
be established in every state. Cash has also been provided for interstate
projects in fisheries, livestock, forestry, seeds, treecrops, research, and
irrigation of the shallow valleys common in the north.
The Bank has installed local senior management and funded institutions such
as the federal agriculture co-ordination unit in Ibadan, which links the
ADPs in each state, the agricultural projects monitoring and evaluation unit
in Kaduna, as well as an agricultural data bank.
Small-scale funding by the UNDP, the FAO and IFAD complements these aims.
The EC has also invested around Ecu200m (Pounds 165m), partly on specific
crops such as oil palm in the south-east and tea on the Mambilla plateau
near Cameroon.
The ADPs are part of a range of government agencies, such as Women in
Agriculture, the directorate for food, roads, and rural infrastructure, and
the national agricultural land development authority. These agencies do not
always square with the aims of official aid. This applies especially to the
land development authority which aims to clear 50,000ha of land in each
state, to be allocated by state governors.
Environmental concerns. Around 900,000 sq km - almost all the land in
Nigeria not under forest cover - is affected by soil erosion. Soil quality
is affected by the pressures of population growth, intensified grain
production and shorter fallow periods. The estimated cost of deforestation,
caused by the encroachment of farmers, is Dollars 750m annually, while
inappropriate use of chemicals costs a further Dollars 600m. Both could be
checked by stopping incentives to use mechanical equipment and chemicals, by
strengthening farmers' land tenure to give them a stake in sustained growth,
and by increasing to market levels the fees for forestry concessions.
Water resources. In the past two decades, Nigeria has spent Dollars 2bn on
large-scale irrigation projects. Out of an intended area of 338,000ha, only
59,000ha are receiving irrigation from these schemes. The public-sector
river basin development authorities are pressing ahead with further
construction of dams in spite of the greater success and lower cost of
small-scale, private-sector irrigation schemes backed by the World Bank.
Market distortions. The aim of SAP was deregulation, but state controls,
subsidies and protectionism persist. Although farm gate prices have been
freed, the government maintains food security stocks at the federal level,
buffer stocks at state level and small storage facilities at local
government level.
The record suggests that the job could be done better by the private sector.
Fertiliser subsidy costs the government about N2.9bn a year, over half the
total agricultural budget.
Fertilisers, whether produced locally by state-owned Nafcon or imported, are
subsidised. About half of the official supply of 1.4m tonnes a year is
unaccounted for because the corrupt system of state distribution has created
a parallel market. Here, fertiliser sells for about three times the official
price or is smuggled to neighbouring francophone countries.
Mr Ernest Shonekan's promise in January 1993 to hand over distribution to
the private sector has not been fulfilled.
The cereals and rice import ban, which stopped large imports of wheat from
the US, was suspended last year until June 1993. But flour mills have been
unable to operate near capacity because of uncertainty over government
policy.
Most of Nigeria is not suited to wheat production, but other staple crops
are in surplus. A ban on the export of cassava and sorghum has been
circumvented by smuggling.
Stop-go policies have also affected the cocoa sector, one of the main
successes under SAP, as well as sugar, production of which has been
distorted by import duties which have oscillated between 5 and 40 per cent.
In the three decades since independence, Nigeria has been transformed from a
large exporter of food to a large importer. SAP has arrested the sharp
decline which began with the discovery of oil, but it has only gone part of
the way towards liberalising the sector.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
