<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (12): Market re-examined - Multinationals
show interest in main sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR ALL the private sector's complaints about the inhospitable nature of
Nigeria's business climate, year after year companies continue to turn in
handsome naira profits.
Last year, the pre-tax earnings of some 70 listed Nigerian commercial and
industrial companies rose 43 per cent, while after-tax earnings were up 40
per cent. Both fell behind the inflation rate of 46 per cent.
While in hard currency terms earnings have plummeted with naira devaluation
since 1986 and will do so again this year.
Despite this, leading multinationals are taking a fresh look at the Nigerian
market, though in some sectors, - banks and pharmaceuticals - there has been
substantial disinvestment. Almost all the US banks have gone, though this
was partly the result of their industry-specific problems at home. In
pharmaceuticals, Boots, Beyer, ICI and Merck have divested, while Wellcome
has signalled its intention to quit, to be followed, industry sources say,
by Roche and CibaGeigy.
But it is not all one-way traffic. Proctor and Gamble has come into the
market through the Vicks group, and Colgate Palmolive may follow. Rothmans
has opened up in tobacco and Nestle is beginning its second substantial
expansion project in recent years. Glaxo is likely to expand with a Dollars
10m injection of new capital from abroad. Nigerian Bottling has raised N100m
offshore in non-voting equity to strengthen its balance sheet and sharpen
its competitive edge.
CMB Toyo Glass Nigeria recently raised N150m in the Nigerian market to
finance the acquisition of African Glass Ltd, and expand and modernise its
production lines. Guinness is considering a Pounds 5m investment, funded
from head office, to refurbish and expand while Cadbury Schweppes is putting
Dollars 7.5m, partly funded offshore with a loan from the Commonwealth
Development Corporation, into a new cocoa processing plant which will
produce cocoa butter for export.
Some of these investments represent balance sheet restructuring and the
bolstering of working capital that is necessary at a time of rapid inflation
and devaluation. The overseas funding reflects the lower cost of capital
abroad though the Nigerian firms are saddled with the foreign exchange risk
and some indigestion in the domestic capital market, where there were more
than a dozen new issues in the first 10 weeks of 1993.
That all this should be taking place against a background of economic crisis
and political uncertainty is explained by three main strategic
considerations. First, with a GDP of some Dollars 30bn Nigeria is the second
largest market in sub-Saharan Africa, after South Africa. Few
multinationals, especially in basic consumer goods, can afford to ignore
such a market explaining why the Rothmans, Colgates and Proctor and Gambles
are showing interest. Guinness, for instance, sells 1m hectolitres of its
stout in Nigeria making it the third largest market after Ireland and the
UK. In the mid-80s, Cadbury was selling more Bournvita in Nigeria than in
the rest of the world.
Second, Nigeria is the logical platform from which to operate an Ecowas
(Economic Community of West African States) strategy. Few manufacturers
export significant volumes directly, and the mere mention of the export
processing zone planned for Calabar, provokes ribald comment from
industrialists, but indirect, smuggled exports are important and growing
and, even if the CFA (French African Community) franc is devalued, as widely
anticipated, Nigeria will continue to have a marked competitive edge in
costs in regional markets. One successful exporter, CMB Toyo Glass, says its
labour costs are less than 4 per cent of turnover. But manufacturers are
among the first to admit that delivery logistics, infrastructure and quality
are significant obstacles to exporting.
Third, intense competition in principal world markets is driving
multinationals into peripheral markets which in less competitive times they
might have ignored. Although Nigerian sales are negligible by global
standards, multinationals cannot afford to allow their competitors a free
ride.
Alongside strategic considerations are the need to reduce import dependence
in an economy where between half and two thirds of industrial inputs are
purchased abroad. Cadbury, which with a technical partner, has a worldwide
patent for producing malted drinks from maize and sorghum, Guinness and
Nestle, have all invested in local sourcing.
Multinationals would invest more, making greater use of state-of-the-art
technology were the Nigerian Enterprise Promotion Decree to be amended
allowing foreign firms majority ownership.
But the main obstacles to greater investment in Nigeria are structural -
infrastructure, the level of risk, investment and operating costs and, above
all, market size.
