<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (15): Industrial production falls - The
failure of import substitution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BY ANY yardstick Nigeria is under-industrialised. In a Dollars 30bn market
with a population of more than 90m people, manufacturing accounts for only
8.5 per cent of GDP, well below the average for countries at this stage of
the development cycle.
Indeed, in the past 11 years manufacturing value added (MVA) has grown at a
mere 1.5 per cent annually, which means that on a per capita basis,
industrial production has been falling.
There can be few more classic examples in Africa of the failure of import
substitution. The latest survey by the Manufacturers' Association of Nigeria
(MAN) covering the first half of 1992 tells the story: capacity utilisation
of 34.5 per cent for manufacturing as a whole, lowest in vehicle assembly,
steel and engineering and electronics and highest in wood and furniture
textiles plastics and rubber, food and non-metallic minerals, primarily
cement,
Over the past three survey periods, imported raw materials have averaged 55
per cent of the total, while value added in manufacturing as a whole was
estimated in 1989 at 46 per cent compared with 92 per cent in the oil sector
and 83 per cent in agriculture.
Aside from mainstream consumer goods the main investment interest in recent
years has focused on downstream oil and gas activities and textiles.
In a high inflation, high devaluation economy, it is hardly surprising that
entrepreneurs should have targeted trade and finance rather than
manufacturing. Pretax returns on investment are highest in trading (up to
100 per cent) followed by construction (50 per cent) and the finance sector
(30 per cent).
Five crucial constraints to industrialisation in Nigeria have been
identified:
Poor profitability relative to trade, finance and construction;
Infrastructural and regulatory constraints which mean that operating costs
are up to a third higher in Nigeria than elsewhere. Investment costs are
estimated to be some 50 per cent above international standards.
The high risk climate of political and economic uncertainty that makes
long-term planning extremely difficult.
The absence of an enabling environment in terms of macro-economic stability,
observance of legal contracts, inadequate patent law provisions, the high
and escalating crime rate, etc.
Restrictions on ownership in the form of the Nigeria Enterprise Promotion
Decrees (NEPD).
There is no quick-fix way out of this morass, though there are at least two
administrative steps the Shonekan government could take during its brief
tenure: first, amend the NEPD, thereby allowing foreign firms already in
Nigeria to have majority ownership of their subsidiaries, and, second,
abolish the existing system whereby new investments must run the gauntlet of
official approval through the IDCC, and setting up an investment promotion
agency to replace the existing approval machinery.
The accelerated depreciation of the naira over the past year will boost
local sourcing and exports, but there are still some hard policy choices to
be made. The privisation agency's gloomy conclusion that the country's six
vehicle assembly plants cannot be privatised because of low capacity
utilisation and deteriorating commercial and financial performance
underscores the need for a new strategy towards capital intensive low-value
added activities where Nigeria has no competitive advantage.
Yet, the federal government has actually increased its investment in
capital-intensive manufacturing, through the recapitalisation of Savannah
Sugar and new investment in the Ajaokuta steel project, the aluminium
smelter, the fertiliser industry and Nigerian Machine Tools.
One of the first tasks of the incoming civilian administration later this
year will be to develop a coherent industrial strategy, which, in all
probability, will mean some short-term de-industrialisation as low value
added, highly protected activities are restructured or allowed to go under.
Industrial growth will have to come from labour-intensive, consumer goods
activities as well as upstream and downstream petroleum and gas-related
manufacturing.
