<DOCNO>FT932-17203</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDACLAH6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930401
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (11): Tough talk by creditors - Balance of
payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S international creditors are faced with a dilemma. Nigeria has no
chance of sustaining non-inflationary growth unless it is granted debt
relief on concessional terms; but the government's recent track record is so
poor that granting debt relief may well mean throwing good money after bad.
Nigeria's current account slipped into deficit last year, further proof of
the macro-economic mismanagement of the past two years. The government's
decision to expand domestic demand at too rapid a pace, and the naira's
depreciation, mean that import values have raced ahead of exports.
Imports grew by 11.6 per cent in 1991 and 7.1 per cent in 1992 while export
values fell by 12.8 per cent and 1.3 per cent respectively. The current
account deficit has slipped from a surplus of 7.8 per cent of gross domestic
product in 1990 to a deficit of 2 per cent last year.
The slide into deficit has been accompanied by a growing capital account
deficit caused by capital flight, debt service obligations and outflow of
some Dollars 3.4bn to buy back London Club debt. The government has been
forced to finance the combined and current and capital account deficit of
Dollars 6.2bn by accumulating debt service arrears and running down its
stock of official foreign exchange reserves.
The IMF estimates that debt service arrears increased from Dollars 2.2bn at
the end of 1991 to Dollars 3.4bn at the end of 1992. The UK reports Dollars
600m in unpaid export credit guarantees. Meanwhile, foreign exchange
reserves have fallen from Dollars 4.1bn in 1991 to around Dollars 1bn by the
end of 1992.
The IMF's recent Article 4 report expects that Nigeria's balance of payments
position will remain weak in the medium term. Even if the government is able
to pursue sensible policies, the IMF estimates that Nigeria will face an
average Dollars 2bn a year financing gap throughout this decade.
The IMF's baseline case assumes that the government is able to institute a
programme designed to bring inflation under control. The current account
returns to surplus in 1997 but the debt service ratio, as a percentage of
exports, never falls below 25 per cent. The result, according to the IMF, is
a cumulative residual financing gap, not covered by reserves or private
capital flows, of Dollars 16.5bn up to 2000.
Higher oil prices would ease the burden - the IMF assumes that a Dollars 1 a
barrel rise in oil prices generates an extra Dollars 0.6bn a year in oil
revenues - but, within a reasonable range of projections, would not close
the financing gap. Conventional debt rescheduling merely postpones the
problem.
The IMF concludes that 'a durable solution to Nigeria's external debt
problem and the achievement of external viability would require debt
rescheduling on concessional terms, including a significant reduction in the
stock of debt'.
Yet Nigeria will not be handed debt relief on a plate, regardless of the
IMF's projections. The Paris Club creditors have made it plain that Nigeria
must first agree a tough and comprehensive adjustment programme with the
IMF, and establish a track record.
The British government has said it will support concessional debt relief for
Nigeria if an IMF programme is signed but not all the creditors are so
amenable. Germany and Japan remain sceptical that a reduction in the debt
stock is needed for external viability.
Nor are the World bank and the IMF confident that an agreement can be
reached soon. The transitional council has said publicly that it would like
to agree a shadow programme with the IMF in April, hoping that a two-month
track record will be sufficient to produce a fully-fledged agreement and
unlock debt relief. But World Bank officials say this timetable is
unrealistic.
The best the transitional council can hope for is a shadow programme which
endorses the government's proposed policy framework but requires a six to
nine months track record before an extended structural adjustment facility
can be signed.
The transitional council is prepared for some hard negotiating. 'The IMF
will tell us they want to see lots of good evidence before they can act,'
says one senior council member. 'But I say, for God's sake help us to
succeed because this is Nigeria's last chance.'
Finance minister Chief Dele Olashore takes a tougher stance. 'If the western
creditors withhold support and want us to commit suicide then they will lose
as well as us. I hope that they are informed enough to prevent that from
happening.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
