<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (7): A sector that needs refor - The
authorities have themselves to blame for an unsound banking system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSMEN, residents and taxi-drivers are unanimous in blaming the 'VI
banks' for the worsening traffic and telephone congestion on Victoria
Island.
Dozens of new banks which sprang up on the island acquired a notoriety in
1990-91 as 'foreign exchange shops', buying foreign exchange at a
'subsidised' price from the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) and selling it to
customers at a handsome premium.
Many were not banks at all, because they had no deposit base and the only
service they provided was to supply foreign currency. With their access to
foreign exchange under the previous foreign exchange allocation system, all
banks were guaranteed a weekly allocation of dollars; and with leading firms
operating literally dozens of bank accounts, in an effort to secure enough
foreign currency to finance essential imports, banking was a low-risk,
high-return business.
Then came March 5, 1992, when the naira was devalued, the parallel market
premium virtually eliminated, and banks could no longer arbitrage between
the official and the free markets. Suddenly, banking became a different
proposition altogether. Firms no longer needed to operate multiple accounts
to be sure of getting their foreign currency requirements, nor could they be
held to ransom and forced to pay a premium for free-market funds, because
the CBN and the autonomous market between them were able to supply the
market's needs.
By the end of the year, the strains were beginning to show, especially as
the authorities forced banks to hold growing amounts of low-yielding
'stabilisation securities'. Those without a sizeable deposit base, by far
the majority of the country's 120-odd banks, found themselves in volatile
market conditions, paying anything from 30 to 80 per cent at different times
of the year, for interbank money, but earning a maximum of 21 per cent on
stabilisation securities. There were reports of 'defaults' in the interbank
market as some of the merchant banks, in particular, were squeezed by high
interest rates on their borrowings and a major reduction in income.
According to the central bank, roughly one third of the country's banks are
now classified as 'unhealthy' or 'distressed', which in at least half a
dozen cases is no more than a euphemism for insolvent. These 40 banks, some
of them the old state-owned banks which have been in trouble for years, and
others from the new breed of VI banks, were barred from bidding at the
weekly foreign exchange auction that was their meal ticket until a year ago.
Recently, however, the pendulum has swung back in favour of the unhealthy
banks. Once again, foreign exchange is being allocated at the auction, this
time on a pro rata basis relative to the bank's application for foreign
exchange. At the auction on March 11, banks were given less than 20 per cent
of their bids, again forcing importers and merchants to scour Lagos for
foreign exchange and to pay a premium for a 'blend' of official market funds
at N25 to the dollar and free-market funds costing as much as N34. For the
disqualified 40 banks, its vital to get back into the auction where there is
easy money to be made.
Clearly, none of this makes for a sound, healthy banking system. The
authorities have only themselves to blame. Until the issue of new banking
licences was suspended in 1991, they licensed just about anyone, provided he
could put down the necessary initial capital N20m until February 1991, and
now N50m. Banks were given until mid-1992 to raise their capital to the new
level, but the Nigeria Deposit Insurance Corporation (NDIC) subsequently
reported that, at the end of 1991, only 16 out of 65 commercial banks and 15
out of 54 merchant banks had raised their capital ratios to the required
levels.
The CBN had neither the expertise nor the resources to provide the level and
extent of supervision necessary, while rapid money supply growth ensured
that funds were not difficult to come by. Although liquidity was not really
an issue, because the foreign exchange traders were able to earn handsome
returns with only minimal liquidity levels, the 1991 NDIC report found that
20 of 116 operating banks had been unable to meet the specified 30 per cent
minimum liquidity ratio.
Last September, the CBN set out six criteria against which a third of the
country's banks were adjudged unhealthy or distressed. The criteria
included: 'sound' management, prudential guidelines, minimum capital, cash
and liquidity ratios, and a new 8 per cent capital adequacy ratio.
Bankers say that some of the unhealthy institutions will not find it
difficult to satisfy the bank inspectors the next time around, and already
one bank has been allowed to return to the auctions. But with money market
conditions set to tighten this year, the weeding-out process by liquidation,
merger or takeover will gather momentum. In its medium-term policy document,
the government accepts the need for moving beyond the classification of
banks to closure or enforced restructuring and more diligent supervision
than in the past.
The return of the foreign exchange market premium may delay the process; but
since any strategy of exchange-rate stabilisation implies a reduction in the
'real' money supply - that is, inflation running well ahead of money-supply
growth over the next year or two - the going will get tougher for all the
banks. Ironically, the stabilisation security technique of mopping up excess
liquidity punishes precisely those banks that the authorities should be
encouraging, the liquid and responsible performers. One merchant banker says
that no less than a quarter of his balance-sheet value is tied up in
stabilisation securities, on which the return is not much more than half his
cost of funds. 'The more liquid you are, the more you suffer'.
The N32bn now held in stabilisation securities (40 per cent of the money
supply) is due to be phased out from April, as the central bank switches to
an indirect system, in the form of open-market operations, to control
liquidity. As that happens and the authorities are forced to pay market
rates for their funds, rather than borrowing from the CBN, pressure on
margins should ease as the banks earn 40 per cent or more on treasury bills,
rather than 21 per cent on stabilisation securities. But at the same time,
credit demand will fall as government borrowing is reduced and as high
nominal interest rates, a falling naira, and declining domestic demand force
traders and manufacturers to cut back their borrowings.
Inevitably, the authorities will soon be forced to abandon their efforts to
prop up the naira, and the arbitrage window being exploited by some of the
banks will slam shut again as it did a year ago. The writing will then be on
the wall for many of the 'unhealthy third'.
