<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (6): Blueprint for change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF NIGERIA'S renewed commitment to economic reform takes root, much of the
credit will go to the participants at a remarkable summit in the federal
capital of Abuja.
For three days in February leaders from the public and private sector,
joined by officials from international development agencies and senior
diplomats, conducted a rigorous appraisal of the economic health of the
nation.
'Your mission,' President Ibrahim Babangida told them in his opening
address, 'is to chart an appropriate strategy and help to put in place other
reforms which are still needed to fully restructure our economy.'
The summit, intended to become an annual event, was the brainchild of Chief
Ernest Shonekan, chairman of the country's transitional council and a
prominent businessman. Inspired in part by President Bill Clinton's
pre-inauguration economic conference in Little Rock and encouraged by
Nigeria's business community keen to assist one of their own, Mr Shonekan
struck an ambitious note: 'We can lay the foundation for a more buoyant
economy for the 1990s and beyond.'
The two days that followed were marked by a sombre analysis of the country's
economic crisis, coupled with enthusiasm about Nigeria's potential.
Participants extolled the virtues of the free market, called for less
government intervention, and advocated measures to attract local and foreign
investment.
Group discussions focused on monetary and fiscal policies, debt management,
capital markets, law and order, and Nigeria's image abroad.
What emerged was a blueprint for change, which will be the subject of
further debate and consultation at regional gatherings and at suitable
venues abroad.
Copies of the summit report (which includes the main speeches, as well as a
list of participants that reads like a who's who of the business sector) are
now available.*
Bringing together such a range of participants at short notice was in itself
no mean achievement.
But in the weeks that followed the limitations on the transitional council's
capacity to implement the Abuja blueprint have become increasingly evident.
A post-summit session is due to take place in Lagos tomorrow at which a
frank appraisal of progress - or lack of it - is expected.
* Report on the First Nigerian Economic Summit, NES Organising Committee, PO
Box 51204, Falomo, Lagos. Tel (234-1) 269-1908 Telex 28220 ARTLAG NG, fax
269-1248. Price N1,200, Dollars 50 air mail, Dollars 75 courier delivery.
</TEXT>
