<PROFILE>_AN-DDACLAH0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930401
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (4): Quick-fix solutions not on offer -
Tony Hawkins assesses the steps taken to translate the economic dream into
reality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT NO time in the past 20 years, and possibly since independence, has
Nigeria had an administration so committed to economic reform. But
commitment alone will not be enough to translate the Abuja Economic Summit
dream into reality. Within weeks of their taking office, it was apparent
that the admirable Mr Ernest Shonekan and his transitional team lacked the
resources, the authority at the end of the day - the military are still
calling the shots - and, above all, the time to do more than outline a
platform for future reform and economic growth.
The challenge is to establish a sufficiently secure economic policy
framework that will survive the return to full-blooded civilian rule. In
just five months, the transitional council has to tackle the twin tasks of
short-term crisis management - stabilising the naira, slowing inflation,
bringing a semblance of order and discipline to Nigeria's public finances -
and creating a medium-term policy framework, an enabling environment within
which sustained growth can be achieved.
It is a formidable task, and, almost certainly, an impossible dream given
the time constraint and the enormity of the inherited economic crisis.
On taking office, Mr Shonekan inherited foreign reserves of under Dollars
1.4bn (less than eight weeks' import cover); a record N44.2bn budget
deficit, escalating foreign debt arrears of more than Dollars 3bn, 46 per
cent inflation and an unsustainable exchange rate.
On the positive side, however, the military also left behind the outline of
a coherent medium-term economic strategy which the Shonekan team hopes to
translate into some kind of formal (a policy framework paper endorsed by the
World Bank and IMF) or informal agreement ( a 'shadow' IMF programme) before
it is forced to leave office. A Bank/Fund team is visiting Abuja this month
to discuss such a programme, but the substantive Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF) programme that Nigeria must have, if it is to get
off the external debt hook, cannot be negotiated with what the international
community sees as a lame-duck transitional government.
At this juncture, there is just no way of assessing the likely economic
policies of a civilian president, since the economy figures only at the
periphery of the political debate. The omens are disturbing, however.
In recent weeks, one frontrunner, Chief Abiola, has pledged to limit debt
service payments to 8 per cent of exports, a second, Ambassador Kingibe, has
come out against removing the petroleum subsidy while a third, Dr Joe Nwodo,
has promised to double Nigeria's exports in the next four years by
exploiting 15 solid minerals and to fix the naira exchange rate.
In Nigeria, the economic policy debate is conducted at two very different
levels. The contrast between the largely hard-headed realism of private
sector participants at the Abuja summit and the popular debate in the media
between presidential aspirants, assorted 'renowned' academic economists,
lawyers and journalists, could hardly be greater.
For the populists, the pillars of a coherent medium-term strategy include a
'realistic' administered exchange rate as distinct from one determined by
market forces, antagonism towards foreign capital and foreign equity
investment, the conviction that because Nigeria is an oil exporter its
citizens deserve the cheapest fuel in the world, and the, sadly justified
historically, belief that any Nigerian government will squander whatever
resources it obtains from taxation and foreign borrowing.
From an economic viewpoint, the optimal outcome would be an extended tenure
for Chief Shonekan and his 'businessman's government'. They understand what
has to be done, though some members of the administration still hanker after
quick-fix solutions that simply are not on offer.
A stiff dose of deflation, fiscal and monetary, lasting at least a year will
have to be imposed. Unquestionably the key challenge is that of budgetary
reform, since the roots of economic crisis - rampant inflation, a
depreciating exchange rate, unstable money markets, unproductive public
investment and the crowding out of private sector investment - lie in a
fiscal deficit averaging 7.7 per cent of GDP since the structural adjustment
programme was launched seven years ago.
The phased removal of the petroleum subsidy, the closer monitoring of public
spending and the planned introduction in midyear of a modified VAT will all
help to curb the deficit, but the structural deficit problem will be
resolved only when Nigeria has secured a debt reduction agreement with its
Paris Club creditors. Last year full debt servicing would have absorbed 133
per cent of federal revenue and only when this is reduced to manageable
proportions will Nigeria escape from the crisis of a yawning budget deficit
and escalating payments arrears, at home and abroad.
Only when the core problem of the fiscal deficit is tackled and an ESAF loan
and Paris Club debt reduction agreement is in place, will a return to
macro-economic stability become possible. Last year, 46 per cent inflation
was fuelled primarily by the naira devaluation on the one hand and the
explosion in government borrowing from the banks, especially the central
bank, on the other. The money supply (M2) increased 57 per cent, largely
reflecting the 96 per cent growth rate of lending to government.
The Shonekan administration, which had no hand in these fiscal and monetary
excesses, is now picking up the tab. According to businessmen, inflation has
accelerated to between 65 per cent and 70 per cent, while the downward
pressure on the naira, driven by excessive liquidity in the banking system,
has widened the parallel market premium from 5 per cent for much of 1992 to
40 per cent.
With a foreign exchange budget of Dollars 4.7bn for the year and dollar
demand running at an annual rate of Dollars 14bn, monetary policy will have
to be tightened and interest rates pushed even higher than the current 45
per cent to 50 per cent borrowing rate to slow inflation and curb domestic
demand. Inflation is going to get a good deal worse before it gets better.
Some packaging firms have doubled their prices in the first quarter of the
year; resumed naira depreciation and the phasing out of the petrol subsidy
will push inflation above 100 per cent in the third quarter, if not sooner,
and even the optimists expect the naira to average N30 to the dollar this
year compared with N16 in 1992.
Given this inheritance there is little the transitional council can do but
tighten the fiscal and monetary taps, and sweat it out while turning a deaf
ear to the cries of pain from all sectors of the economy. After growing very
rapidly - 8.5 per cent a year between 1988 and 1990 - GDP growth slowed to 4
per cent in 1991/2 - and will turn negative this year with the OPEC cut in
oil production, falling investment as high nominal interest rates and credit
restraint start to bite and as import growth is reined in and public
spending declines substantially in real terms.
The balance of payments deteriorated from rough balance on current account
in 1991 to a deficit of some Dollars 500m last year, but with the outflow on
capital account of some Dollars 3.4bn to buy back London Club debt, there
was a huge Dollars 5.7bn deficit on capital account. The overall deficit of
Dollars 6.2bn was financed partly by accumulating Dollars 2.6bn in arrears
and running down the reserves to Dollars 1.35bn from almost Dollars 6bn a
year earlier.
The current account situation has since worsened forcing the Central Bank to
cut the weekly supply of dollars at the currency auction to only Dollars
60m, to clamp down on open account and bills for collection trade, freezing
an estimated Dollars 1bn to Dollars 1.5bn in payments due to foreign
suppliers, and to defer payments for letters of credit until 90 days after
the shipment of goods to Nigeria. These ad hoc measures and the continuing
accumulation of official arrears - Dollars 600m owed to the UK, Dollars 500m
to France and Dollars 400m to Germany - have done nothing for the country's
creditworthiness nor do they get to the roots of the problem.
It is a bleak picture. Chief Shonekan is not going to turn the economy
around in his few months in office, but he is far and away the best option
on offer.
Mr Shonekan given the time, authority and resources is the man most likely
to force through the deflationary package followed by a medium-term strategy
for sustained recovery.
 ------------------------------------------------------------
BALANCE OF PAYMENTS (DOLLARS BN)
 ------------------------------------------------------------
                            1990     1991     1992
 ------------------------------------------------------------
Exports                     13.9     12.1     12.0
(of which oil)             (13.5)   (11.6)   (11.5)
Imports                      7.1      7.9      8.5
