<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Survey of Nigeria (1): Promises, promises - Nigeria's
civilian-led transitional council needs the soldiers' backing if it is to
implement the hard choices the Abuja recovery plan requires. As the country
prepares for presidential elections, Africa Editor Michael Holman finds that
deeds have yet to match words
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S attempt to put its faltering economic reform programme back on
track is in jeopardy.
Without greater commitment on the part of the military government that
stands behind the country's transitional civilian administration, the effort
will fail, conceivably imperilling the transition to civilian rule due to
conclude on August 27. Without such commitment, Nigeria's sceptical
creditors will withhold assistance and the burden of a Dollars 29bn external
debt will become intolerable. Deepening austerity will exacerbate existing
religious and regional tensions, conceivably threatening the thrice-delayed
transition to civilian rule.
Once again, Nigeria has promised to mend its ways. Last December, an
transitional council was mandated by President Ibrahim Babangida to restore
economic discipline, plan for the future, and run the country until the
winner of June's presidential elections formally takes over in August.
This time the promise carried more weight. The council and its officials
represent the acceptable, respectable face of Nigeria. The chairman, Chief
Ernest Shonekan, is a distinguished and popular businessmen, assisted by
some able colleagues with distinguished careers, and enjoying the backing of
the private sector.
But, as the halfway stage of the council's tenure approaches, it is in
danger of being labelled the best goverment Nigeria never had. Nominally it
is in charge. In reality, it is subservient to the soldiers who have run
Nigeria since December 31, 1983.
The council got off to an encouraging start. The 1993 budget, due to be
delivered on January 1, was efficiently and imaginatively redrafted. What
emerged three weeks later was a ringing reaffirmation of the necessity of
reform, the virtues of the market economy, and the overriding need for
prudent management.
'We must make some hard choices now to preserve the gains of the structural
adustment programme and restore some good measure of stability to the
economy,' Mr Shonekan warned the national assembly.
It was followed not long after by an unprecedented gathering of business
leaders, summoned to the capital, Abuja, for what was billed as Nigeria's
first economic summit. In two days of straight talking, with President
Ibrahim Babangida attending the opening session, the gravity of Nigeria's
economic crisis was made clear. The reform programme launched in 1986 was in
deep trouble. Among the most revealing indicators was the outcome of the
1992 budget: the forecast surplus of N2bn turned out as a deficit of
N44.2bn.
Money supply had increased by 49 per cent during the year, pushing inflation
to 46 per cent. Exchange rate policy had in turn been undermined, and the
naira was buckling. Foreign exchange reserves had fallen from Dollars 4.1bn
in 1991 to around Dollars 1bn by the end of last year - barely two months
import cover - partly because of Nigeria's costly involvement in the
Liberian conflict.
'What we need now is a strong commitment to implementation, and to keep
faith with the reform programme,' General Babangida told the summit. No one
reminded the general that he had promised much the same a year earlier. A
devaluation of the naira from 10.5 to 18 to the dollar had been accompanied
by pledges of fiscal restraint, prudent monetary policies, public sector
rationalisation, and curbs on state spending. The 1992 deficit speaks for
itself.
Despite the gloomy picture, delegates took heart from the prospect of a
fresh start under a technocratic administration. Yet a very different mood
prevailed at the follow-up session in Lagos last month. In the intervening
period the council had fudged one critical hard choice, and blundered in an
area in which it should have expertise. Exchange rate policy was in evident
disarray, illustrated by a Central Bank decision to nullify the results of
one of its foreign exchange auctions on the grounds that bids for the dollar
were 'outrageously' high.
Equally disturbing was the bank's decision to clamp down on open account and
bills for collection trade, freezing more than Dollars 1bn in payments due
to foreign suppliers. Payments for letters of credit were to be deferred
until 90 days after the shipment of goods to Nigeria.
Speaker after speaker criticised the council's performance: 'The Abuja dream
has turned into a nightmare,' complained one industrialist.
Although Mr Shonekan himself displays an indefatigable optimism, the
enormity of the task is starting to weigh down some of his colleagues. 'The
politicians are against us, the civil service is against us, the soldiers
are against us,' concluded a weary senior official.
The politicians do not want to be boxed in by economic reforms which they
see as unpopular with the electorate, he explained. More important, he
suspected that the members of the House of Representatives and Senate,
elected last year, are wary of transparency and accountability which reduce
opportunities for patronage. Similar concerns are shared by the poorly paid
civil service.
Among the military, few officers relish the prospect of civilian overseers.
Nor is the electorate especially enthusiastic, seeing them as the lesser of
two evils. 'The army has been politicised, and politics commercialised,' as
one Nigerian puts it.
The toughest choice facing the council, and central to economic reform is
the need to raise domestic petrol prices. At N0.7 (three US cents) a litre,
smuggling is rife (the pump price in neighbouring Benin is N9.7) and
production costs are not covered. Lost revenue would nearly cover the 1992
budget deficit.
Whatever the economic imperative behind a price rise, the political risk is
enormous. The money would be 'chopped', say Nigerians - meaning it would end
up in politicians' pockets - and trade union leaders and students have
threatened to take to the streets. The decision to increase petrol charges
has been taken in principle; whether it can be implemented remains to be
seen.
What adds to Mr Shonekan's difficulties is the fact that in the time
available he has nothing tangible to offer Nigerians, who have had to endure
a gruelling decade.
Per capita income has fallen from Dollars 1,000 in 1980 to under Dollars
300. The naira, once worth more than a dollar, is worth less than a nickel,
and weakening. External debt has grown by 50 per cent in spite of commercial
debt buy-backs and conversion.
Not surprisingly, while creditors and donors offer Mr Shonekan moral
support, they demand a track record before delivering the carrot - part
write-off, part soft-term rescheduling of Paris Club debt.
An essential precondition to rescheduling is an IMF agreement. Most
observers rule it out in the time available. Even if it were possible, would
it last? The incoming government cannot be tied into an agreement it did not
negotiate. And judging by their comments at the hustings, neither Mr Bashir
Tofa nor Mr Moshood Abiola, the presidential candidates of the National
Republican Convention (NRC) and the Social Democratic Party (SDP)
respectively, seems prepared to pledge continuity in economic reform.
Time is running out on what seasoned observers believe is Nigeria's last
best chance of securing an economic recovery. As one concerned Nigerian put
it: 'If not Shonekan, who? If not now, when?' But it is General Babangida
who ultimately has to make the hard choices, and to do that he must keep his
promises.
</TEXT>
