<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Hotel sector shaken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUSPENSION of shares in Queens Moat Houses sent shock waves throughout the
hotel sector and prompted speculation about the group's future. Queens Moat
said it was suspending its shares 'pending clarification of the company's
financial position'.
After the dust had settled, speculation began over which rival companies
might benefit from the situation. Bass was the immediate favourite,
following its recent agreement extending the deal to convert Queens Moat
hotels into Holiday Inns.
While analysts ruled out a full-scale rescue by Bass, some selected
purchases could be made, they thought. Queens Moat now runs 20 Holiday Inns
in Europe. Other names touted included Forte, which has long coveted a major
presence in Europe.
Queens Moat is due to report its final results next week, although analysts
were growing increasingly gloomy as the day wore on that the situation was
so serious that they will have to be postponed.
While the nub of the problem appeared to be a preference dividend payment of
around Pounds 7m, due yesterday, analysts close to the company suggested
that the problem might have occurred as a result of debt restructuring talks
being held with the group's chief lenders. Queens Moat's debts are estimated
at more than Pounds 1bn by leisure specialists, who say the company's
gearing is around 100 per cent.
Queens Moat shares were suspended at 47 1/2 p. Although some cherry-picking
of the assets may benefit selected companies, the fear that a major player
had run into difficulties hit sentiment in the sector. Forte tumbled 9 to
192p, Friendly Hotels 6 to 155p, Ladbroke 4 1/2 to 181p and Rank
Organisation 8 to 655p. Bass shares came off 10p on news of the suspension,
but later recovered with support from a programme trade to finish 3 ahead at
546p.
