<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Moscow's gold reserves now at
320 tonnes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR YEVGENY Bychkov, head of Russia's Precious Metals and Stones Committee,
said yesterday that the country's official gold reserves consisted of 150
tonnes held by the central bank and 170 tonnes with his committee.
This figure compares with the rock bottom level revealed about one year and
a half ago of 240 tonnes.
In an interview with the Financial Times, covering diamonds as well as gold,
he also said he would be urging improvements in Russia's relationship with
De Beers in talks to be held in Moscow today.
Finally, he suggested that Star Technology Systems, an Australian company
which has set up a joint stock company with Lenzoloto, a state-owned
Siberian gold producer, was unlikely to be allowed to exploit Russia's
biggest hard rock gold deposit.
The joint stock company, Lena Gold, has been approved by the State Property
Committee. It is now waiting for the Russian government to declassify secret
information about the Sukhoi Log deposit's reserves so that it can pay the
first Dollars 20m instalment of its Dollars 250m investment.
Mr Bychkov said, however, that he and the State Geology Committee were
preparing a new draft decree which, if approved by the government, would
exclude foreign companies from the development of the Sukhoi Log deposit,
organise a tender for Russian companies, and commit the government to cover
some of the costs.
'We have dozens of other gold deposits which can be exploited by foreign
companies. But this one must be exploited by ourselves,' he said.
Mr Bycchkov claimed that Lena Gold had not fulfilled conditions set by the
government for the Australians to take part in the development of Sukhoi
Log.
Apart from Mr Bychkov's objections, Star faces claims from the State Geology
Committee that Lena Gold has not fulfilled the conditions for a licence to
exploit Sukhoi Log to be confirmed by the committee. Nor has Lena Gold
sought to do so, arguing that documents have been confirmed by local
authorities.
Controversy also continues to emerge from Russia's relationship with another
foreign company, De Beers. Mr Bychkov said he was intent on bargaining to
improve the terms of a five-year contract, signed in 1990 with the Soviet
Union and renewed by Russia, whereby 95 per cent of Russian exports of rough
diamonds have to go through De Beers.
But Mr Sergei Ulin, a director of Almazy Rossii-Sakha, the state-owned
company which runs the diamond industry and is in charge of relations with
De Beers, said that evaluations had not found the agreement to be
'non-beneficial to our national interests'.
He said that Russia could increase prices fetched for its diamonds by
improving the efficiency of its diamond polishing industry, adjusting output
volumes according to varying international demand, and preventing smuggling.
