<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZINC came under late pressure on the LME, with three-month metal pushed
below the psychological support level of Dollars 1,000 a tonne, although
sell stops were not triggered. Underlying producer support might cushion
falls, but the bearish fundamental picture of rising stocks might see prices
testing contract lows of Dollars 987, dealers said. COPPER prices were
steadier. The market was helped by expectations of support below Dollars
2,160 a tonne, although stiff resistance around Dollars 2,170 prevented any
further upside movement. ALUMINIUM was consolidating after Tuesday's decline
to 14 1/2 -month lows. Some consumer interest was seen above Dollars 1,140 a
tonne for three-month metal. Copper's stability was also supportive. NICKEL
eased back from midsession highs, as recent gains attracted profit-taking,
although the market remained firmer after investment fund interest. New York
raw SUGAR was mixed at midday after opening lower on profit taking. But
traders said tighter global supplies, expectations for sharply lower Cuban
output and bullish technical factors were pointing to higher prices ahead
and had deterred aggressive selling.
Compiled from Reuters
