<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: US grain sales to Russia eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER SUBTLE adjustment in US Department of Agriculture credit guarantee
policy this week will allow more grain to be shipped to Russia during the
next few months.
The action seems to be part of a programme to warm up US export channels
that froze when the former Soviet Union stopped making interest payments on
its US-backed grain loans four months ago.
The move comes before President Clinton's meeting with President Boris
Yeltsin this weekend. Grain traders expect the US to produce a new aid
package at that meeting facilitating additional grain shipments to Russia.
The USDA amended its credit guarantees to exporters so that 600,000 tonnes
of US maize and - sold before interest payments on US-backed loans stopped
in late November - could be shipped.
Banks had been reluctant to issue letters of credit to back the
USDA-registered sales for fear of incurring non-guaranteed risk.
Without the letters, exporters were unable to deliver the grain. The USDA
amendments will move the grain, but increases the agency's exposure to
Russia's grain defaults, which are expected to reach Dollars 1 bn by June.
The restored sales, which are worth about Dollars 250m, and this month's
massive US food donations will keep grain flowing to Russia while the
Clinton administration and G7 policy makers review debt rescheduling
options.
During March, the US announced donations of 520,000 tonnes of wheat, 210,000
of corn, and 87,000 of rice. An cash sale to Russia of 120,000 tonnes of
soyameal, made last week, will also enter shipping channels soon.
Separately, Canada is arranging barter sales of its feed wheat to Russia.
Canada suspended grain sales to the the Soviet Union in September when it
fell behind on its Dollars 1.5 bn credit line with the Canadian Wheat Board.
All of this was bullish news to farmers who would like to see the US-Russian
grain trade normalised. But prices for next year's maize and soyabean crops
were lower after the USDA announcement, while wheat prices received only a
minor boost.
</TEXT>
<XX>
