<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: London coffee pact talks fail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS ON an international coffee agreement with market support measures
collapsed yesterday evening in London.
'There is no more time and no more space to reach a compromise,' said Mr
Arnoldo Lopez, chairman of the International Coffee Organisation committee
which had been specially set up to look for any areas of agreement between
producers and consumers.
Yesterday was the deadline set by delegates to negotiate an agreement to
replace the current pact, which expires at the end of September.
The full ICO Council was meeting late into last night. However, Mr Lopez
said it was unlikely that the council would be making any decisions last
night on the ICO's future, but it would decide to reconvene soon. Options
before it include the establishment of a purely administrative agreement
such as is run by the International Sugar Organisation.
World coffee markets have already discounted the latest talks, which were
not expected to succeed. London robusta prices closed higher yesterday just
before the news, and New York arabicas were up by well over 1 cent a lb in
early trading.
However, prices are less than half the 120 cents a lb of July 1989, when the
ICO export quota system collapsed. Producers are estimated to have lost more
than Dollars 10bn in revenues since then.
Mr Valdemar Leao, from the Brazilian delegation, said that producers had got
as close as they could to the consumer position.
However, he complained: 'They did not move. In the last 12 months the only
items we have agreed were when we agreed with the consumers. The pace of the
negotiations was impossible. We have agreed on three articles and we need
agreement on 71.'
At the end of the last talks in February Brazil, the largest producer,
obliquely blamed the US, the biggest consumer, for the deadlock. In the
ensuing weeks producers have lobbied the new US administration intensively.
Early yesterday evening the consumers would make no comment on the collapse
until they had agreed a common position. But one producer delegate said that
the consumers had played their hand very badly. 'They were playing for an
extension - they are rather shocked that they did not get it.'
Mr Lawrence Eagles, analyst with GNI, the London futures broker, said the
attitude of consuming countries towards commodity agreements as a form of
aid for developing countries had changed. But he predicted a backlash. 'The
US will be surprised at the amount of flak it has to take over this,' he
said.
</TEXT>
