<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Government Bonds: Gilts strengthen on success of Bank's
Pounds 3bn auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UK government bonds surged by over a point yesterday on news that the Bank
of England's Pounds 3bn auction of 20-year gilts - the biggest-ever auction
of UK government stock and the first in the government's new programme of
gilt issuance - had been well-received.
The strong rally prompted the Bank to take advantage of the favourable
market conditions by announcing a further Pounds 600m of 8 per cent stock
due 2003 available for sale with effect from today.
Gilt-edged marketmakers described the Bank of England's auction of the 8 per
cent gilt due 2013 as a 'big success', pointing to the relatively high cover
of 1.96 and the lack of a 'tail'.
The 'cover' is the ratio of bids to the amount of stock on offer, so a high
cover suggests that demand from dealers and investors was strong. The 'tail'
at an auction is the difference between the average accepted yield and the
highest accepted yield. The Bank said both the average and the highest
accepted yield were 8.53 per cent at yesterday's auction. The lowest
accepted yield was 8.52 per cent.
'The auction result exceeded people's wildest dreams,' said Mr Chris
Anthony, economist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew.
Long-dated gilt prices gained a point on the auction announcement and
remained firm during the afternoon. The Liffe gilt future rose from 105.07
to a high of 106.17 in heavy trading before ending at around 106.13.
Ten-year gilts gained about half a point, while short-dated issues
underperformed the rest of the market as hopes of an imminent cut in the
base rate faded. As a result, the gilt yield curve flattened yesterday.
Gilt-edged marketmakers said demand at yesterday's auction came mainly from
domestic institutions, although they noted some foreign buying interest too.
The market had been particularly anxious about the auction, as it is the
first one to take place in the Bank of England's new funding programme of
bigger and more frequent auctions.
GERMAN government bonds ended lower on the day, reflecting market
disappointment at the Bundesbank's small cut in the repo rate yesterday.
The Bundesbank accepted bids for DM84.6bn in its tender, and cut the lowest
allocated rate for 13-day funds to 8.17 per cent from 8.25 per cent at the
previous week's repo. The central bank drained a net amount of DM13.8bn from
the market. Dealers said the market had hoped for a larger decline in the
repo rate.
The Liffe bund futures contract opened at 95.58, and climbed to a high of
95.68 early in the trading session, but drifted lower in the course of the
day to end at around 95.38.
US Treasury prices weakened in thin trading yesterday as investors chose to
stay on the sidelines before tomorrow's important employment figures.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  7/32 at 102
1/2 , yielding 6.922 per cent. At the short end of the market, the two-year
note was also lower, down  1/8 at 99 13/16 , to yield 3.957 per cent.
Dealers put the modest declines down to the Chicago purchasing managers'
February manufacturing and employment indices, which came in stronger than
expected.
The market ignored news of a 1.4 per cent rise in February factory orders
and a 0.5 per cent rise in the February leading indicators, increases that
were in line with expectations.
The day's data aside, investors' attention remained fixed on the
all-important jobs report for March, which will be released tomorrow.
Analysts are expecting the figures to show a 100,000 increase in non-farm
payrolls.
THE combination of a strong yen and stock market weakness in Tokyo helped to
push up Japanese government bond prices yesterday morning, although the
market later fell back to close lower on the day on hedge-selling by
dealers.
The yen strengthened against the dollar during Tokyo trading, prompting the
futures contract to rise from its opening price of 108.65 to a high of
108.86. However, bond prices later weakened on hedge-selling after the
monthly government bond auction, and the futures contract ended Tokyo
trading at 108.51.
The futures contract picked up again in London trading, reaching 108.81 as
the yen appreciated against the dollar.
The ministry of finance auctioned Y800bn of 10-year bonds with a coupon of
4.5 per cent, up from 4.2 per cent at the previous auction. This marks the
first time that the coupon has been raised in nearly a year. The 10-year
bonds were auctioned at an average yield of 4.458 per cent.
In the cash market, the benchmark No 145 issue yield opened at 4.2 per cent,
moved in a range of 4.185 to 4.220 per cent, and ended at 4.22 per cent.
</TEXT>
