<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Capital Markets: Repsol sets offer price at
Pta2,735 after high demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG demand for Repsol equity has allowed the Spanish energy group to
waive a discount in its global offering to institutional investors and set a
price of Pta2,735 (Dollars 23.68) a share, its closing share price on
Tuesday on the Madrid stock exchange.
The issue is likely to be one of the largest this year to be aimed at
international institutions, and will realise Pta110bn.
Repsol will be issuing 40m shares, which is the maximum amount of equity
that it was authorised to offer by the government. The book-building
process, in which Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank, acted as global
co-ordinator with Banco Bilbao Vizcaya as joint co-ordinator, reportedly
indicated a demand for 70m shares.
Repsol said a total of 35m shares had been allocated to the five tranches of
the offering and that it was issuing a further 5m 'greenshoe', or
over-allotment, shares - 15 per cent of the total offering - in an
over-allocation option in order to stabilise the market.
In the allocation, the US tranche, led by Goldman Sachs, is offering 14.5m
shares and 8.45m shares are being offered in the UK where SG Warburg and
Banco Santander de Negocios are co-lead managers.
The continental European tranche, jointly led by Paribas and Credit Suisse
First Boston, totals 6m shares; the Spanish one, which has Banco Central
Hispano as lead manager, amounts to 4.25m; and the rest of the world
tranche, which is being led by Morgan Stanley, has been allocated 1.8m
shares.
Madrid stockbroking firms FG and Ibersecurities, which had earlier hoped
that Repsol would set the offer price at Pta2,700 a share, yesterday
recommended the shares at their higher price as an attractive long-term buy
with a target of Pta2,900 to Pta3,000.
The global offering represents 13.3 per cent of Repsol's equity and it will
reduce the government's shareholding in the energy group from 54.4 per cent
to 41.1 per cent.
</TEXT>
