<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Engen looks unlikely to invest
in fuel project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ENGEN, the energy arm of South Africa's Gencor group, yesterday said it was
unlikely to exercise its rights to acquire a 30 per cent stake in the
controversial R12bn (Dollars 3.8bn) Mossgas synthetic fuels project.
Mr Bernard Smith, chairman, said it 'looks as if we will be making a
negative decision on Mossgas'. Engen has until the end of 1993 to decide. He
said the investment did not appear commercially sensible because Mossgas
would not be viable without a considerable state subsidy.
Earnings at Engen, meanwhile, rose by 10 per cent in the first half to the
end of February. However, Mr Rob Angel, managing director, said the results
were not what the company had hoped for. He predicted that Engen would
achieve real earnings growth for the full year.
Turnover rose by 10.4 per cent to R3.56bn from R3.23bn, and operating income
advanced 42 per cent to R270m from R190m thanks to a better wholesale margin
and cost containment.
These gains were offset by a fall in net financing income to R13m from R67m,
leaving net income 10.7 per cent higher at R228m compared with R206m.
Earnings per share rose by 10.1 per cent to 147 cents from 134 cents and the
dividend was increased by 10 per cent to 55 cents a share from 50 cents.
Mr Angel said sales had been flat - below expectations of 3 to 4 per cent
growth. He attributed this to South Africa's economic climate, a hiatus in
the name change from Mobil to Engen and problems with various township
sights.
The refinery, he said, had had a 'very disappointing' first half. Teething
problems following an upgrade were exacerbated by frequent power failures.
Crude volumes through the refinery were thus about 20 per cent below
forecast.
</TEXT>
