<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Bank Leumi returns to black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY MALTZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK LEUMI, Israel's second-largest bank, yesterday reported a return to the
black with net profits of Shk210.4m (Dollars 76.1m) for 1992, after losing
Shk85.4m in 1991, writes Judy Maltz in Jerusalem.
This turnround was the result of a decrease in the bank's bad debt provision
to Shk573m from Shk900m. A law passed by parliament had forced the bank to
make large write-offs in 1991 for the country's semi-collective farms.
Total assets were Shk78.4bn at the end of 1992, an increase of 6 per cent
from a year earlier.
United Mizrahi Bank, Israel's fourth-largest bank, yesterday posted trebled
net profits of Shk111.5m in 1992 from Shk35.7m the year before.
The main factor behind the rise was a sharp drop in its bad debt provision
to Shk97.3m from Shk182.2m. Its return on equity was 15 per cent.
</TEXT>
