<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Brokers line up for SDollars
10bn telecoms offer - The flotation which launches Singapore's privatisation
programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF there's one thing that a Singapore broker craves, it is excitement.
The local corporate scene is dominated by a small number of companies - only
nine listed on the local exchange have shareholder funds of more than
SDollars 1bn (USDollars 613m). While most of these companies can be expected
to turn in good results each year, they are seen as steady, if not
spectacular, performers.
But things are changing. After much official foot dragging, Singapore is
about to embark on a privatisation programme which is likely to change
completely the character of the local market over the next two to three
years.
Singapore Telecom (ST), the state-owned telecommunications and postal
service, is first on the seller's block. The ST floatation is being billed
as the largest public listing yet in the south-east Asia region.
When floated, it is estimated that ST will be valued at SDollars 10bn to
SDollars 15bn. 'The Singapore Telecom float will add about 15 per cent to
total market capitalisation overnight,' said one broker. 'It will be the
biggest thing to hit the exchange in a long, long while.
Singapore Airlines, partially privatised by the government in the mid-1980s,
will be the only listed company comparable in size. SIA now has a market
capitalisation of SDollars 12bn.
The government has not set a date for the flotation, but all indications
point to July or August this year. About 25 per cent of ST is likely to be
floated, with about 15 per cent available to foreigners, the rest reserved
for Singapore citizens.
The government proposes selling shares to Singaporeans at a discount, and is
putting SDollars 200m into a compulsory savings fund so as to encourage a
wide uptake of shares.
Dr Richard Hu, Singapore's finance minister, says people will be given
incentives to hold on to shares rather than seek to make a quick profit.
'The discount will be structured to discourage stagging. The last thing we
want to see is what happened in the UK, where people took shares at a
discount and got out. That defeats the whole purpose of the exercise.'
There seems little doubt that the ST issue will be massively oversubscribed.
ST is not a plodding state behemoth that the government is anxious to rid
itself of.
Since it was reorganised a little over 10 years ago, ST has built Singapore
telecommunications into the most modern and efficient in south-east Asia.
The company has invested heavily in modern technologies such as packet
switching, integrated services digital networks (ISDN), fibre optic
distribution, international leased circuits, video-conferencing and
interactive videotext systems.
While maintaining minimal domestic rates, and with some of the lowest
international rates in the world, ST has managed to accumulate considerable
cash reserves. In the year to March 31 1992, ST's operating income was
SDollars 2.48bn, a 12 per cent rise over the previous year. The net pre-tax
surplus before exceptional items rose 18 per cent to SDollars 1.33bn.
To consolidate Singapore's position as a regional telecommunications hub, ST
plans a SDollars 3.7bn five-year investment programme which includes setting
up a third satellite earth station and more worldwide submarine cable links.
Singapore-based analysts see ST's earnings growing by between 12 and 15 per
cent in the medium term. But the company does face some problems. Singapore,
with a population of under 3m, offers little room for expansion. The city
state already has one telephone to every two people.
ST will be up against considerable competition as it seeks to expand its
services overseas. But through Singapore Telecom International (STI), formed
in 1988, ST says it has already entered into 14 ventures in 11 countries,
with total investments of SDollars 250m.
While these projects are on a limited scale, concerned mostly with data
communications and paging services, considerable opportunities are available
in China, Vietnam and Indonesia - markets already well-known to Singapore.
The government is determined that the ST flotation will take place without
any problems. It is being watched as the guide for a spate of further
sell-offs of state enterprises. The Port of Singapore Authority (PSA) and
the electricity and gas divisions of the public utilities board are likely
to be partially privatised over the next two years. The Singapore mass
transit system and portions of other, mostly financially successful state
enterprises, will also be listed.
In recent years, Singapore has been overshadowed by the excitement of other
fast-expanding regional markets. Kuala Lumpur in nearby Malaysia, now has a
market capitalisation almost twice that of Singapore. But all that is likely
to now change, giving the Singapore broking community a bout of much delayed
excitement.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Singapore Telecom.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SGZ  Singapore, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4813 Telephone Communications, Ex Radio.
    P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
