<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Eastman Kodak accuses Sony of
patent infringement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EASTMAN Kodak has filed a suit against Sony, one of Japan's leading
electronics manufacturers, in a patent infringement dispute that could have
broad implications throughout the consumer electronics industry.
Kodak alleges that Sony's video cassette recorders, camcorders (video
cameras) and other audio and video recording products infringe upon a patent
that the US company obtained in 1981 covering a new type of recording head
for magnetic recording devices.
Industry analysts say that the same technology is widely used throughout the
consumer electronics industry. Kodak declined to comment on whether it has
granted patent licenses to other manufac-turers.
According to the complaint, which was filed in Texas, Kodak has been
attempting to reach a licensing agreement with Sony since the late 1980s.
Kodak is asking the court to issue an injunction to prevent Sony from
selling products in the US that allegedly infringe its patent.
The US company is also seeking treble damages, although it does not specify
the amount, and has asked for a jury trial. Sony's sales in the US last year
were over Dollars 6bn, of which VCRs and video cameras represented a
significant portion. Sony America declined to comment on the suit.
The damages covered by the Kodak claim could be substantial, said Mr Jack
Kelly of Goldman Sachs. He said the suit against Sony might encourage other
manufacturers of recording equipment to seek licenses from Kodak.
Kodak is awaiting a decision from the Japanese patent office on whether it
will grant a similar patent in Japan. The patent application, which was
filed in 1981, has been opposed by several Japanese companies.
</TEXT>
