<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: CarnaudMetalbox improves 15%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARNAUDMETALBOX, the French packaging company whose 25.3 per cent
shareholder MB-Caradon, the UK building products and security printing
group, is considering selling its stake, increased net profits by 15 per
cent to FFr976m (Dollars 174m) in 1992. That was in spite of tough trading
conditions and the effect of devaluations against the franc.
Mr Jurgen Hintz, president and chief executive officer, said the results
showed that CMB was recession-resistant.
He said that even without any recovery in its markets in 1993, the group
should show further progress. There were gains to come from cutting costs,
saving working capital and using FFr1.5bn of tax losses.
Mr Ernest-Antoine Seilliere, head of CGIP, the Frech holding company which
has a 25.3 per cent stake in CMB, said if MB-Caradon sells, CGIP aims to buy
7 per cent and an associate investor would buy a further 6 per cent. The
Paris stock exchange had said this would not necessitate a full bid.
Sales in 1992 fell 3 per cent to FFr 24.8bn, but would have been 2 per cent
ahead on constant exchange rates. Lower resin prices hit prices for plastic
packaging but margins in the division improved pushing the group operating
margin up from 9.4 per cent to 9.9 per cent.
Operating profits rose 2 per cent to FFr 2.5bn. Lower reorganisation costs
of FFr262m compared with FFr389m and a fall in interest charges to FFr 642m
from FFr 672m led to a 12 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to FFr 1.7bn.
Earnings per share were FFr 12.07 up 14 per cent. A dividend of FFr4 is
proposed, an 8 per cent rise.
</TEXT>
