<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Not-so-big bang in Tokyo - New
broking rules take effect today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE pre-publicity in the late 1980s had heralded today as Japan's 'big
bang': the wall between brokers and bankers was to be torn down, and
financial deregulation would bring tough competition and rich opportunities.
Instead, today's 'bang' in the Japanese financial system will be barely
audible - though it is likely eventually to have widespread repercussions. A
Financial System Reform Law, applying from today, will slowly dismantle the
barriers between different types of financial institution, thereby
increasing the pressure on inefficient institutions.
The limited changes that take effect today are partly a product of the
times. Reform was conceived when Tokyo stock prices were surging and there
seemed to be ample profits for all. But legislation has come after three
years of falling prices, leaving most brokers with losses and many banks
with bad loans.
It is also the Japanese way to take change slowly, easing institutions into
new areas and attempting to keep existing players content. The legislation
may be important, but the ministry of finance never allows itself to be
rushed on such matters.
Only long-term credit banks, such as the Industrial Bank of Japan, are now
allowed in the securities markets, and even then only to underwrite and deal
in bonds; they still have no right to handle stocks or even deal in
equity-linked bonds. Commercial banks, such as Dai-Ichi Kangyo and
Mitsubishi Bank, must wait another year - perhaps longer - for these limited
privileges, which may be reviewed, the finance ministry says, in 'two to
three years'.
Meanwhile, brokers are now allowed into trust banking. The four leading
houses - Nomura Securities, Daiwa Securities, Nikko Securities, and Yamaichi
Securities - have plans for new subsidiaries, which are expected gradually
to be given greater freedoms by the ministry.
But there will no quick profits for bankers or brokers, though the ministry
insists that the new subsidiaries should be making a profit after three
years. One banker going through the motions of establishing a new operation
said that, given the choice, the company would like to delay the opening of
its new subsidiary.
'Now is really not the best time for us to be doing this. We are limited in
what we can do, and will not make money, but we can't afford to offend the
ministry. If we had said we had decided to wait a year, they could have made
life difficult for us,' the banker said.
Institutions are expected to make formal applications to the ministry in the
next few weeks, providing details of capital, the identity of executives,
and branch plans. In May, or perhaps June, the ministry will allow the
subsidiaries to open.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
