<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Total plunges to FFr2.85bn on
low oil prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL, the French oil group, yesterday confirmed that it suffered a steep
decline in net income to FFr2.85bn (Dollars 518m) last year from FFr5.81bn
in 1991, due to low oil prices and adverse exchange rates.
The fall in profits comes at a delicate time for Total, which last year
staged a FFr9.5bn share sale in which the then socialist government reduced
its holding from 31.6 per cent to 15 per cent. The group is a candidate for
full privatisation by France's new conservative administration.
Sales fell to FFr136.61bn in 1992 from FFr143.02bn in 1991, while operating
profits slipped to FFr7.32bn from FFr10.33bn over the same period. Earnings
per share fell from FFr27.50 to FFr13.50.
The worst affected area of activity was refining, where operating profits
fell sharply to FFr2.15bn from FFr4.87bn. Total said the impact of the
squeeze on refining margins was mitigated by improvements in marketing.
The group also suffered a steep decline in its trading and Middle Eastern
business, where operating profits almost halved to FFr567m from FFr1.04bn.
However, Total managed to maintain operating profits at FFr2.94bn in
exploration and production. The chemicals division saw profits rise to
FFr1.66bn last year from FFr1.49bn in 1991, mainly as a result of
rationalisation.
The reduction in operating profits contributed to a fall in cashflow to
FFr9.95bn from FFr13.65bn.
Gearing rose to 31 per cent from 25 per cent.
Coface, the French overseas export credit guarantee agency, saw net
consolidated profits rise by 11.2 per cent to FFr157.8m in 1992 from
FFr141.9m in 1991.
The company, which is controlled by the French government, earlier this year
gained a new shareholder in Societe Commerciale de Reassurances, France's
largest reinsurance group, which bought a 20 per cent stake.
Mr Pierre-Yves Cosse, chairman, said that group sales rose by 39 per cent
from FFr1.2bn in 1991 to FFr1.66bn last year, although on a constant
structure the increase would have been significantly lower at 12.5 per cent
to just FFr1.34bn.
</TEXT>
