<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / International Company News: Tampella disposal ends link with
forestry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FINLAND'S Tampella group is ending a century-long involvement in forestry
through a FM3.6bn (Dollars 609m) sale of operations to Enso-Gutzeit, one of
the country's leading pulp and paper groups.
The agreement cuts Tampella's debt burden sharply and leaves it free to
concentrate on its international metal engineering business. It also makes
Enso one of Europe's top three newsprint manufacturers and the leading
corrugated board producer in Scandinavia.
Enso is acquiring Tampella Forest and Tambox Europe and lifting its stake in
Sunila, a pulping company, to 47.5 per cent from 20 per cent. It is taking
over FM2.6bn in debt and paying FM1bn, FM800m of which will be funded
through a new share issue.
The deal involves a reshuffle of state-owned assets as the state has a 57.8
per cent stake in Enso and holds more than 90 per cent of Tampella shares.
The Bank of Finland, which holds the Tampella shares through an earlier
rescue of Skopbank, has made it clear that it does not want to be a
long-term industrial owner and the disposal should help it find new owners
for the remaining business.
The operations being sold had combined sales of FM3.35bn in 1992, and though
lossmaking last year, are expected to return to profit in 1993. Tampella
Forest is Europe's leading manufacturer of uncoated wood-containing book
papers and its third-largest producer of special newsprint, with operations
in Finland, Germany and Spain. Tambox Europe specialises in corrugated board
and has eight mills in Finland, Sweden and Italy.
The main effect of the deal will be to give Enso an enhanced position in
newsprint production, as it will have a 1.2m tonne capacity when combined
with a mill being built in Germany. It will also bolster its position within
packaging and saw-milling.
'Advantages will be gained through streamlining and through a more intensive
use of marketing,' said Mr Jukka Harmala, Enso chief executive.
</TEXT>
