<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK Company News: Calor ahead of forecasts at Pounds 33.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALOR GROUP, the liquefied petroleum gas distributor, yesterday reported
better than expected results for the year to end-December 1992, bolstered by
a stronger performance in the second half.
Pre-tax profits fell to Pounds 33.6m from Pounds 45m in 1991 after
exceptional charges of Pounds 14.8m (Pounds 7.2m) to cover redundancies and
the write down of stock as part of the group's substantial two-year
restructuring programme.
The exceptional charges last year were as reported at the interim stage and
comprised Pounds 11.4m to pay for gas busi-ness redundancies and other
reorganisation costs, and Pounds 3.4m related to a write-down of Air
Separation stock.
An unchanged final dividend of 6p is proposed, maintaining the total for the
year at 12p. The dividend is just covered by earnings per share of 12p
(18.1p).
However, Mr Michael Davies, chairman, said the directors made their
recommendation in the light of buoyant earnings in the core gas business,
the strength of the group's balance sheet, and the fact that the main
restructuring of the group was complete.
Turnover for the year fell by 14 per cent to Pounds 311m (Pounds 362.2m) due
partly to a reduction in the tonnage of gas sold, but mainly to lower
selling prices.
Operating profits slipped to Pounds 49.6m (Pounds 54.8m).
Finance costs were again reduced, with net interest charges falling to
Pounds 1.2m (Pounds 2.6m). This reflected lower interest rates coupled with
a substantial reduction in capital expenditure and tight controls over
working capital.
Year end net borrowing was reduced by Pounds 10m despite further investment
in the Air Separation business and the Pam Gas Central European partnership
with Calor's main shareholder, SHV, the Dutch investment company which owns
46.2 per cent of the stock, and Primagaz, the French LPG distributor.
</TEXT>
