<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK Company News: Frederick Cooper gains from reduced
interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REDUCED INTEREST charges helped Frederick Cooper, the West Midlands-based
metal finishing, architectural hardware and electrical products group, start
its move out of recession with a 7.6 per cent increase in pre-tax profits
before exceptional items, its first increase for three years.
After interest of Pounds 380,000 (Pounds 647,000) pre-tax profits for the
six months to January 31 were Pounds 1.77m.
Last time's Pounds 1.95m was inflated by a pension fund contribution of
Pounds 400,000. The figures were prepared under the FRS 3 accounting
standard.
Turnover was slightly down at Pounds 40.1m, from Pounds 41.4m, but Mr Eddie
Kirk, chairman, noted that the break-even point in all parts of the business
had been lowered as costs had been reduced.
Firmer control of working capital and a reduction in stocks helped cut
borrowings from Pounds 7.7m to Pounds 4.2m, giving gearing of 21.9 per cent
at the period end, compared with 31.2 per cent last July and 41.9 per cent
in January 1992.
Signs have emerged of an increase in orders. Mr Kirk said that the group had
just had its best quarter for over two years.
Fully diluted earnings were 2.5p (2.8p) after exceptional items or 2.4p
before them. The interim dividend is lower at 0.7p, against 1.5p, as the
group reverted to its normal policy of paying one third of the likely total
at the halfway stage.
</TEXT>
