<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK Company News: Macdonald Martin warns of setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Macdonald Martin Distilleries, producer of Glenmorangie malt
whisky, fell 53p to 390p yesterday after the company warned of a sharp
decline in full year profits.
Pre-tax profits for the year which ended yesterday are expected to be about
Pounds 4m compared with Pounds 8.6m for 1991-92.
The company said it intended to maintain an unchanged final dividend of 6.6p
for A shares and 3.3p for B shares. The price of the B shares fell 50p to
600p
Trading in the second half had continued to be affected by the price
discounting and lack of consumer confidence that had cut interim pre-tax
profits by 42 per cent, said Mr Neil McKerrow, managing director. 'Sales of
proprietary whiskies have not reached expectations and the anticipated
renewal of industry supply contracts has not materialised as a result of
declining trading conditions.'
Bulk blend sales, particularly to Australia and the US, had suffered volume
and margin pressures, though losses had now been stabilised. Bottled blend
volumes were ahead but there had been a substantial reduction in
profitability.
Glenmorangie volumes had fallen 12 per cent in UK duty free. Sales in other
markets were stable, with encouraging performances in Japan, Germany, Spain
and the Netherlands, but increased marketing expenditure had reduced
profits.
</TEXT>
