<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK Company News: Wace incurs losses of Pounds 24m after
provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUBSTANTIAL property write-downs and restructuring provisions caused Wace,
the UK-based pre-press and specialist printing group, to report a pre-tax
loss of Pounds 28.4m for the 1992 year and pass its final dividend.
However, Wace surprised the market by deciding to retain its US subsidiary,
after stating last December that it would be offered for sale at about
Dollars 100m (Pounds 70m). The group also decided against writing down the
value of its industrial properties, reducing the Pounds 37m provision it
identified in December by Pounds 12m.
The results were presented by Mr Trevor Grice, who took over as chief
executive in November - nine months after the sudden departure of his
predecessor, Mr John Clegg.
The DTI has still not published its investigation into share dealings
conducted in the name of some of Mr Clegg's relatives, but Wace again
emphasised that the inquiry had no connection with the group.
Mr Grice said that when he arrived, it was planned that Wace should sell
both its US operation - which accounted for nearly half the group's
operating profit last year - and the UK labels business to reduce the
group's gearing level, which currently stands at nearly 200 per cent.
The new chief executive quickly decided not to sell the labels business and
also won the agreement of the group's lenders not to sell the US business,
both of which disposals would have diluted earnings. He said: 'The US
operation is a very good business - it would have broken my heart to sell
it.'
Mr Grice said that the Pounds 37m property write-down flagged in December
was a 'worst-case' position, following a revaluation of the group's
properties in November.
The group had proceeded with the write-down of its investment property from
Pounds 28m to Pounds 8.7m, and made Pounds 5m provision to cover the
disposal of vacant leaseholds.
However, after discussing the issue with his property advisers and auditors,
Mr Grice said the group had decided not to write down the value of the
property owned and occupied by the group by Pounds 11.3m, as it considered
no permanent diminution in value had occurred.
Sales grew from Pounds 308.6m to Pounds 321m in the year to December 31, and
the pre-tax loss of Pounds 28.4m compared with profits of Pounds 9.8m. The
group also made a provision of Pounds 4.1m to cover redundancy and
reorganisation costs.
A total of 211 jobs have been shed since November, reducing the workforce to
4,840. Losses per share of 44p compared with earnings of 1.4p.
Mr Frans ten Bos, chairman, said it would be imprudent to forecast increased
activity in the group's main markets, but added: 'We are cautiously
optimistic that we will record a marked improvement in our trading
performance in 1993.'
COMMENT
Reversing the decision to sell the group's US subsidiary was unexpected, but
looks positive. Wace insists it could have achieved its target price of
Dollars 100m, but was able to persuade the group's lenders that it makes
more sense to keep a profits earner which should benefit quickly from
recovery. Analysts forecast full-year profits of Pounds 15m, which puts the
shares, down 2p to 90p yesterday, on a very modest prospective multiple of
about 10. The new chief executive has cut costs and insists the underlying
business is sound. Assuming no more nasty surprises lie in store, the shares
could bounce back rapidly as advertising markets recover.
</TEXT>
