<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK Company News: Scholl static despite charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHOLL, the personal healthcare products group, managed to maintain its
pre-tax profits last year despite difficult trading conditions and
exceptional charges.
Pre-tax profits were unchanged at Pounds 16.1m after exceptional charges of
Pounds 1.58m to cover disposals and other items. Earnings per share slipped
to 12.1p (13.1p) but the proposed final dividend is increased to 3.7p (3.5p)
making a total of 6.3p (6p).
Turnover at Pounds 151.3m (Pounds 144.4m) was up 4.8 per cent - 2.2 per cent
higher in local currency terms - bolstered by two acquisitions. Those were
the Scholl retail operations in Canada acquired from Schering Plough, and
Gerard House, the UK-based herbal medicines business.
Gross profits increased to Pounds 85.7m (Pounds 83.3m) although gross
margins slipped to 56.7 per cent reflecting the changing business mix and
the increased volume of licensed products.
Profit before tax and exceptional items rose by nearly 10 per cent to Pounds
17.7m (Pounds 16.1m) helped by a full year's interest on the Pounds 24.5m
1991 rights issue proceeds and lower working capital. Net interest income
was Pounds 2.49m (Pounds 360,000) last year.
The exceptional charges, which were expected, covered Pounds 1.99m of costs
associated with the disposal of the Isabelle Lancray subsidiary and six
French/Benelux retail outlets, plus a Pounds 1.06m non-cash adjustment
related to goodwill previously written off to reserves. These were offset by
the release, under the FRS 3 accounting standards, of provisions of Pounds
1.47m held in connection to a 1990 disposal.
Mr Neil Franchino, chief executive, said that although 1992 had been a
challenging trading year, the group had succeeded in its objectives of
stabilising turnover, protecting profitability and pursuing its three point
strategy for growth.
This strategy involves brand development, acquiring new businesses and
developing additional licensing and disribution businesses.
</TEXT>
