</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / IBM says four big plants are 'surplus'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines says four of its big European manufacturing
sites are surplus to its requirements.
The plants include some of IBM's best known European operations: Havant in
the UK, which makes small memory units; Montpelier in France, which makes
silicon chips and large mainframe computers; Valencia, which makes small
mainframes in Spain; and the printer plant at Jarfalla in Sweden.
The company plans to make these plants 'independent business units', run by
their local managements. The experiment will only continue if the plants can
show themselves capable of returning a satisfactory profit. This plan,
however, was drawn up before the arrival of Mr Louis Gerstner, IBM's newly
appointed chairman and chief executive.
He starts his new job today, with a meeting of top managers to review the
state of IBM's operations and the measures it is taking to improve its
performance.
Mr Gerstner is expected to take a more aggressive approach to cost cutting.
The future of the four European plants identified as surplus is therefore
uncertain.
A total of 4,867 jobs at the plants are at stake. In the US, IBM this week
notified some 2,600 workers at its mainframe computer and semiconductor
plants in New York state they have lost their jobs. These are the first
involuntary redundancies in IBM's 79-year history.
An additional 3,400 employees have agreed to take early retirement.
IBM has said it plans to eliminate more than 25,000 jobs worldwide this
year, including 10,000 in Europe, as part of a restructuring plan announced
in January.
However, industry analysts expect Mr Gerstner to increase the target to as
many as 100,000, which would require large scale redundancies throughout
IBM's operations.
IBM's European operations will be under intense pressure to improve their
performance. Last year, IBM made operating profits of Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds
1bn) in Europe, down from Dollars 3bn the year before. Restructuring
charges, however, forced a loss of Dollars 1.7bn.
Mr Renato Riverso, head of IBM Europe, was not optimistic yesterday about
the region's business prospects for 1993. He was not confident that growth
would return in 1994. He said the original target of 10,000 job cuts in
Europe could be achieved without closing manufacturing plants or forced
redundancies.
</TEXT>
