<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Queens Moat shares suspended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Queens Moat Houses, the UK's second biggest hotel group, were
suspended yesterday at the company's request as it announced it was
postponing a Pounds 7m dividend payment.
Queens Moat had been due to report results next Wednesday. and yesterday's
move raised fears in the market about them. A statement from the company
said that the share suspension was 'pending clarification of the company's
financial position'.
The group has heavy debts, taken on to finance expansion. They are given as
Pounds 927m in the accounts for 1991, but forecast to go over Pounds 1bn for
1992 by some analysts. This would give gearing close to 100 per cent.
The company has a large amount of D-Mark denominated debt which has been
affected by sterling's devaluation. Analysts had been forecasting final
pre-tax profits of around Pounds 85m.
Queens Moat shares have mirrored the fall in the leisure sector. They hit an
all-time low of 27.5p in August after its debt levels surprised the City and
have since climbed to yesterday's suspension level of 47 1/2 p. Ten months
ago they were 92p.
At the beginning of February Mr Martin Marcus, Queens Moat's deputy
chairman, sold 1.1m shares for Pounds 629,500, the day before the company
went into its closed period ahead of the results.
Mr Marcus said then that he had sold the shares to fulfil personal
obligations and that the transaction was not related to any aspect of the
group's performance.
Queens Moat Houses recently extended an agreement with Bass under which the
former will convert four of its UK hotels and four on the European continent
into Holiday Inns.
Yesterday's dividend payment was deferred on the 7.5 per cent convertible
cumulative redeemable preference shares. Trading was also halted in all
classes of convertible and debenture stock.
Investors expressed concern yesterday about a further interest payment of
Pounds 11m due today on the company's Pounds 215m 10 1/4 per cent debenture
stock.
At the last independent valuation, in December 1991, the properties backing
the debenture were valued at Pounds 377m, though UK hotel prices are
estimated to have fallen by 20-30 per cent since then.
Lex, Page 22
Market, Back Page
</TEXT>
