<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / E German employers pull out of steelworkers wage deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WAGE PARITY between east and west German workers moved further away
yesterday after steel industry employers pulled out of an agreement with
unions.
Employees in steel, electrical and engineering, which make up the three main
sectors of the east German economy, have been hit by the employers' refusal
to pay steelworkers a 21 per cent wage increase which was due today.
IG Metall, the giant engineering union, responded by calling for warning
strikes throughout eastern Germany in protest against the action.
Arbeitgeberverband Stahl, the steel employers' association, voted to end a
contract made with IG Metall and east German managers in March 1991.
The contract, also agreed with Gesamtmetall, the electrical and metal
employers' association, would have brought eastern German wages up to
western German levels by April 1994.
Gesamtmetall, which had been due to pay eastern German electrical and metal
employees a 26 per cent wage increase today, had broken the contract in
early March on the grounds that eastern Germany's economy had sharply
deteriorated. IG Metall earlier this week called for warning strikes in the
metal and electrical sectors.
Officials from both employers' associations yesterday said they could not
afford to pay such wage increases in view of low productivity levels - about
70 per cent below west German levels.
'We propose to offer the employees a 9 per cent increase, which is in line
with inflation in eastern Germany,' said Mr Philipp Vossen, a spokesman for
Arbeitgeberverband Stahl.
He added: 'Our decision ends the timetable towards income parity. The
present wage demands would have slowed down any future investment plans.'
IG Metall officials yesterday denied that their wage demands, and the threat
of an all-out strike later in the month, would postpone growth, and slow
investment in east Germany.
'We cannot ask our members in eastern Germany to accept low wages, but pay
western German prices,' said Mr Gerd Schulz, an IG Metall representative.
The threat of strikes in eastern Germany arising from high wage demands
coincided with the publication of a joint report issued by the German
Institute for Economic Forecasting in Berlin and the Institute for World
Economy in Kiel.
The report showed how high wage demands, linked to continuing low
productivity, would depress growth, stem investment, and stifle the
fledgling small and medium sized enterprises in eastern Germany. 'Wage costs
are the Achilles heel of the eastern German economy,' says the report,
adding that there is hardly any gap between labour costs and output per
head.
Output may fall 7%, Page 2
</TEXT>
