<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / China steps up pressure on Britain over Hong Kong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA STEPPED up the pressure in its diplomatic row with Britain yesterday,
renewing its warnings over trade relations and taking further steps towards
setting up a shadow authority for Hong Kong.
Mr Li Peng, the Chinese premier, said at the end of a meeting of the
National People's Congress, that Sino-British trade could suffer because of
the plans by Mr Chris Patten, Hong Kong's governor, to introduce greater
democracy in the colony.
He also said China was establishing a preparatory committee to facilitate a
smooth transition to Chinese rule over Hong Kong in 1997, and hinted that it
might be set up earlier than expected.
Western officials and figures in the Hong Kong democratic reform movement
fear that China may be planning to establish a shadow government in Hong
Kong to compete with Britain in the lead-up to China's takeover in 1997.
This would undermine the position of Mr Patten, who will hold talks with
senior EC officials in Brussels tomorrow and on Friday before flying to
London to meet UK prime minister Mr John Major.
On trade, Mr Li said: 'I hope that our economic relations would not be
seriously affected.' But he added: 'If the situation continues to
deteriorate, I'm afraid we can't entirely rule out the possibility of
economic co-operation being affected.'
Mr Li Lanqing, vice-premier and former trade minister, issued a similar
threat last month.
Mr Li Peng, whose second five-year term in office was confirmed by the
Congress, China's parliament, also sought to use a Dollars 1.2bn (Pounds
840m) trade deal reached this week with Germany, covering the purchase of at
least 12 Airbuses and other equipment, to exert pressure on Britain.
'That shows what a huge market China can offer,' Mr Li told reporters in
Beijing. 'I believe that British businessmen will also be interested in such
a big market.'
Beijing has been infuriated by the planned reforms advanced by Mr Patten,
which it claims are at odds with understandings reached earlier with London.
Mr Li hinted that an original plan to form the working committee in 1996 may
be brought forward in the light of difficulties with Britain.
Mr Li was equivocal in remarks to reporters about timing, saying that the
purpose of the preparatory committee was to ensure a smooth transition to
Chinese rule to preserve Hong Kong's prosperity. 'According to our original
plan we should establish a preparatory committee in 1996,' he said. The
congress's working committee on Hong Kong would decide when it might be
established.
Politicians in the colony expressed disquiet at Beijing's apparent intention
to push ahead with the committee.
</TEXT>
