<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / UK acts against Islamic bank: Concern at Bank of England -
Pounds 83m will go back to depositors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ONLY bank in Europe run on Islamic principles announced yesterday that
it is to stop taking deposits and return Pounds 83m to 10,000 depositors
after failing to resolve a dispute with the Bank of England over how it
should be supervised.
The London-based Albaraka International Bank, wholly owned by a Saudi
sheikh, said the Bank of England was concerned it could not be supervised in
line with international standards because of its structure.
The Bank is thought to have been worried in the wake of the collapse of the
Bank of Credit and Commerce International that the controlling management of
Albaraka appeared to be in Saudi Arabia although it did not operate as a
bank there.
The move, which follows the administration of Equatorial Bank and the
winding up of the Mount Banking Corporation last October, further reduces
the number of banks which specialise in lending to Asian businesses in
Britain.
Mr Keith Vaz, Labour MP for Leicester East, said he was 'very concerned'
that banks serving Asians in Britain were ceasing to trade. Mr Vaz called
for a select committee inquiry into the supervision of such banks.
Albaraka is one of 22 banks owned by Dallah Albaraka Group, the Jeddah-based
family holding company of Sheikh Saleh Abdullah Kamel. It operates in
accordance with Moslem law by not charging interest on loans, but instead
adopting the Islamic murabaha practice of making set transaction profits.
The bank, which has assets of Pounds 191m, made a pre-tax loss of Pounds
6.8m in 1991 after making Pounds 6.7m provisions against bad debts. Sheikh
Kamel, sole owner of a number of businesses with a combined asset value of
Dollars 6bn (Pounds 4.2bn), injected Pounds 15m of new capital.
Sheikh Kamel said yesterday that he hoped the Bank would accept a new
ownership structure he intended to propose in June, under which other
British shareholders would dilute his shareholding to below 10 per cent.
'For me, it is not important how much of the bank I own. The most important
think is to enable Moslems to practise their religion in their business and
to show that there are good things in Islam,' said Sheikh Kamel.
He said the bank had been negotiating with the Bank of England's supervision
department since the adoption of the Basle concordat in July, which called
for consolidated supervision of banks operating in several countries.
Sheikh Kamel said Albaraka had offered to bring in other Islamic banks as
shareholders, or to accept the Bank of England as its consolidated
supervisor, but all its suggestions had been rejected.
The Bank said it could not comment on its supervision of individual banks.
</TEXT>
