FT  01 APR 93 / The Lex Column: Queens Moat
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It would be rash to draw too many conclusions for the hotel sector from the
troubles of Queens Moat. The company has always had a weakness for taking on
new properties. That explains its past propensity for rights issues and its
present heavy indebtedness. It may be that its German expansion, which
seemed such an advantage at the height of the UK recession, is catching up
with it. Investors will clearly have to wait a while to find out. Meanwhile
they must envy the good fortune of Mr Martin Marcus, deputy chairman, who
sold 1.1m shares to meet personal obligations at an average price of just
over 57p before the company entered its closed season in February. That
compares with a suspension price of 47 1/2 p.
