<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / The Lex Column: UK gilts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's gilt auction turned out more successful than the authorities
could have dared hope. One can discount the high cover ratio: it may simply
reflect rogue bids designed to pick up paper on the cheap. The minimal
difference between the highest accepted price and the average is a different
matter. That points to solid demand.
Perhaps UK institutions have decided that the inflationary outlook is good
enough to make an 8.5 per cent yield on long-dated paper attractive. There
must be some who feared that, even with the more frequent auctions, the
opportunity to buy long-dated gilts will not come up that often. Perhaps,
too, the market had been deliberately oversold since the budget by traders
looking for cheap auction stock.
The danger is that an element of the demand came from fickle sources like
international hedge funds attracted by the steep UK yield curve. If so, the
authorities should beware. With this auction under its belt, together with
sales to banks and calls on existing issues, it could start the new
financial year with getting on for Pounds 10bn already covered. That is good
for confidence, but there is a long way to go.
</TEXT>
