<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Leading Article: G7's Russian gamble
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IN RUSSIA, amid the turmoil and confusion which has characterised the past
fortnight, two conclusions can be drawn with some certainty. First, the
threat of hyperinflation is growing by the day. Second, Russia's apparently
reform-minded government cannot hope to restore some semblance of economic
and political stability, and start to restructure the economy, unless it
receives substantial western financial help as soon as reforms begin.
Western governments are right to be cautious. But they must be ready and
willing to act decisively if the balance shifts decisively in the reformers'
favour.
For the moment, the west is right to limit its support to words. The
unstable balance of power between President Boris Yeltsin and his opponents
make it doubtful that the reformers have the political clout to pursue
reform, even with external aid. Nor can the parliamentarians planned April
25 referendum, in its current unrealistic form, or President Boris Yeltsin's
alternative plebiscite, be relied on to resolve this power struggle.
Even after 18 months of Mr Yeltsin's rule, the central bank remains opposed
to reform. Despite calls for resignations at the bank from Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Fyodorov, it is still increasing credit at the rate of 20 per
cent a month, financing the budget deficit and keeping enterprises afloat at
the expense of accelerating inflation.
Yet while western governments are right to be cautious, they would be wrong
to be inactive. The success of the reformers' draft programme will depend as
much on the organisation and resolve of the western members of the Group of
Seven industrialised countries as on the reformers. The west should use the
coming weeks to draw up a joint economic strategy with Mr Fyodorov and his
team, and arrange multilateral funds which can be disbursed quickly once the
programme begins.
This requires a shift in western strategy. The G7 and the International
Monetary Fund have spent the past year waiting for the Russian government to
establish a track record before releasing notionally available aid. This
strategy is misconceived. The Russian government can only bring inflation
under control by halving the flow of central bank credits. But this can only
occur, in the absence of alternative sources of finance, through huge cuts
in social spending or mass unemployment, neither of which are politically
conceivable.
Only with up-front western aid, in the region of Dollars 2bn-Dollars 3bn
over the next three months, can the government bring inflation under
control. This aid should only be disbursed when the G7 governments are
confident that the central bank has stemmed the flow of credits to
enterprises. And future aid flows, preferably conditional on deeper economic
reforms, must be cut off if the government fails to meet its budgetary
targets. But only by filling the budget gap, and thus stabilising the
exchange rate, can the Russian government persuade investors to hold roubles
rather than dollars and stem the flight of capital to Swiss bank accounts.
This is the enlightened, if risky, strategy. The alternative is for the G7
to procrastinate, using the caution of the rule-bound IMF as an excuse for
its inaction while the reforms wither. The west's reputation in Russia will
then deteriorate further, leaving Europe to deal with the fall-out from
Russia's inevitable and dangerous journey through hyperinflation to
political disintegration.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
