<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Leading Article: Local councils
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY'S INTRODUCTION of the new council tax for funding local authority
expenditure is notable for the absence of controversy. The advent of its
predecessor, the poll tax, was marked by non-payment campaigns, civil
disobedience and even riots. It created chaos in many town halls, choked
some courts with enforcement proceedings and contributed to the downfall of
Mrs Margaret Thatcher. Against the gloomier prognostications of critics, the
council tax seems to have enjoyed a relatively painless birth, ushering in a
period of truce between central and local government which is sorely needed.
Both sides can claim credit for this. Local government has been determined
to make the new system work, despite misgivings about the complexities of
discounts for single-adult households. Council leaders have recognised that
they were drinking in the last chance saloon: the continuing independence of
local government could not survive another poll tax fiasco. They have also
strained to keep spending increases down - with only three councils said to
be in danger of capping for over-spending.
The government's contribution was in designing a system which is more
convincing about its fairness than the poll tax ever could be. It also
defies attempts to produce headline figures for the new tax, leaving most
people blissfully unaware about whether they would be better-off or poorer
as a result. A relatively inexpensive transitional relief scheme has limited
the increases paid by households this year to between Pounds 1.75 and Pounds
3.50 a week. And stringent spending limits have been imposed on councils to
ensure that the change in local taxation has not meant a leap in bills. The
lessons of the poll tax were well learnt in Whitehall.
This apparently painless transition to the new tax coincides with other
signs of an improving relationship between central and local government.
Ministers have spent much of the last year signalling an end to the
hostilities of the 1980s. Councils have become more entrepreneurial in using
the discipline of contracting-out to improve the efficiency and
effectiveness of their services.
Power continues to move towards the centre with the recently announced
police reforms and the increase in schools opting-out of local authority
control. Today also sees more than 550 further education, tertiary and
sixth-form colleges pass out of local authority control, becoming
independent bodies funded directly by the government. However, the movement
of power is not all one-way: responsibility for care in the community is
passing down to councils, also from today. This offers local government an
excellent opportunity to demonstrate their ability to deliver vital services
locally. It should not be fumbled, whatever councils' misgivings over the
funding.
Further challenges lie ahead, including the reorganisation of local
government to provide a single local council for every part of the country.
The tax base of local authorities needs to be extended, since the council
tax will raise less than a quarter of the money they spend. This gearing
means that small increases in spending require the sort of huge increases in
local taxation which so discredited the poll tax.
However, further change should be gradual and incremental. A period of
stability is needed in local government, not least to clear up the mess left
by the poll tax. A decade of warfare between town halls and Whitehall has
profoundly damaged local government. Repairing local democracy will need
care and skill if its political legitimacy is to be restored.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    GOVT  Taxes.
</TP>
