<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Personal View: Budget makes waves in the North Sea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN LOVEGROVE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the Budget, the chancellor revealed plans to make changes to the North
Sea tax system, changes which are fundamental and came without warning. The
question that has to be asked is, are these proposed tax changes bad for the
nation which, after all, owns the oil and gas reserves? The answer is yes,
if they remain unmodified, although not necessarily for the reasons that
some oil companies have been giving.
The most aired argument has been that the proposed abolition of petroleum
revenue tax (PRT) relief for exploration will significantly reduce drilling
activity. This is undeniable, but is it bad for the nation? No. Over the
past few years the likely return on total exploration expenditures, pre-tax,
will prove to be negative.
What has saved those more technically lax companies has been the fact that
the government has been paying between 75p and 83p in the pound for most of
their drilling through tax reliefs. The change in the rules should force
some of the companies to become more technically focused, and appreciate
more fully high-quality acreage and explorations.
If the industry really wishes to argue the point about drilling, it should
concentrate on the unemployment that will be created by the fall in
activity. For if the abolition of the tax relief on drilling occurs as
suddenly as is currently proposed, the loss of jobs within a year could be
measured in thousands.
For their part, some politicians might argue that the reduction in the rate
of PRT on existing fields will give the oil companies a windfall profit. It
is true to say that the income to companies from PRT-paying fields will
increase, but this is generally no bad thing. It should ensure that many
fields are kept in production for longer than they might have been
previously. Equally importantly, the government's share of the cost of
abandoning fields will fall as a result of the rate reduction.
Why, then, are these changes bad for the nation? Simply put, they introduce
considerable uncertainty to an industry which is characterised by lead times
that can be measured in numbers of government life-times. Inevitably, this
will reduce the attractiveness of the North Sea compared with a growing list
of countries elsewhere that compete for the industry's money.
One specific concern is obligation wells. When a company is awarded a
licence by the government, it agrees to drill a certain number of wells in
order to test the prospectiveness of that acreage. Implicitly, such an
agreement is made under the assumption that tax laws of the time will remain
unchanged. To change the laws after the licence award, but before such wells
are drilled, is an effective breach of the underlying terms of contract.
Unless the government redresses this position, it runs the serious risk of
the companies paying less attention to the licensing authorities in the
future. Given the increase of opportunities elsewhere, the government should
realise that, longer term, it will need the companies more than they will
need it.
While one solution might be for the government to waive all current
obligation wells, another would be to allow companies to relieve the cost of
obligation wells against PRT, provided such costs are spent within two
years. This is in line with government treatment for wells that are are
already contracted. It would also ensure the wells are drilled and allow the
unemployment that will be linked to the slowdown in exploration to be phased
in over a longer period.
Another concern is the abolition of PRT on new fields. While the great
majority of new fields would not have paid PRT, one has to wonder whether a
later government will allow those companies lucky enough to develop large
fields to take home the operating income net only of corporation tax, the
full rate of which is currently 33 per cent. From my perspective I would
have to say that there is no chance of this happening. The real danger is
that PRT will be reintroduced, or that royalty will no longer be waived or
that some new form of tax will be designed. The government should,
therefore, keep PRT alive for these new fields. It is a flexible, fair and
known tax system.
With the North Sea now well into maturity, it is right for the government to
consider making some changes to the fiscal regime, and the direction that it
is now proposing is the correct one. It should, however, be more ethical in
the phasing-in of the abolition of the exploration relief, and should
reconsider the idea of abolishing PRT for new fields. Failure to make these
changes will result in a gradual run-down of this important domestic
industry.
The author is director of Lovegrove &amp; Associates, adviser to the upstream
petroleum industry
</TEXT>
