<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Observer: Picked off the shelf
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
High Street retailing is the sort of business which lends itself to a heavy
turnover in chief executives. Most recently, Kingfisher lost its finance
director, Archie Norman, to Asda while Sears poached Liam Strong from
British Airways. Retailing thrives on fresh blood.
However, the transfer market in CEOs tends to be dictated by adversity. It's
hard to remember the last time that one apparently well-run retailer poached
a chief executive from another. Hence the interest in Alan Smith's move from
Marks and Spencer to the chief executive's chair at Kingfisher.
In one respect it's surprising that more M&amp;S chieftains have not defected
before. Smith is 52 and has been on the board since 1978. He is only one of
17 executive directors and, however good he is, it's unlikely that he will
ever get a shot at the top job at M&amp;S. Sir Rick Greenbury, 56, has only been
doing the job for a couple of years and is surrounded by capable types.
Hence the attraction of Kingfisher. It is Britain's fourth biggest store
group and in terms of its 60,000 staff is a similar size to M&amp;S. Smith, a
well-respected retailer, will have a chance to run his own show at last.
Or will he? One has only to look at companies such as Glaxo and Tate and
Lyle to see that imported chief executives can have a relatively short shelf
life when working for a strong executive chairman. Kingfisher's executive
chairman, Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, will be almost as much on probation as the
new boy.
</TEXT>
