<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Letter: Londoners facing dangers of increasing
disenfranchisement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Councillor JULIE FITZGERALD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, It is indeed the case that, increasingly, many of us in London local
government are looking to the rest of Europe for inspiration as we ponder
the bleak future for the town halls on offer from the government ('Too many
bodies spoil the broth', March 29).
Taking the Channel tunnel rail link terminus as just one example, Camden
Council, the planning authority for the area, suggested at the outset that
the viability of St Pancras should be studied along with other options. A
joint planning process might well have brought us to what seems now to be
the current conclusion without several years' delay and costs incurred.
But the government continues to combine extreme centralist tendencies -
London policy co-ordinated by a secret cabinet subcommittee - with an ironic
embrace of corporatism in London First and London Forum, and quango-isation.
Quangos with minimal elected membership now control Pounds 7.5bn-worth of
public money in London and nationally administer more public resources that
the local government sector.
The government opposes council representation on London Forum despite the
fact that it will take under its wing the London Tourist Board, which
receives Pounds 300,000 annually from local authorities through the London
Boroughs Grants Committee. Police authority proposals further weaken council
representation, and the important Maastricht measure specifying seats for
councillors on the committee of the regions was dismissed by ministers as a
'technical' issue only.
Where should Europe point us? Towards public-private partnership at local
level, towards decentralisation and 'subsidiarity', but above all towards a
recognition of the role of local government as more than a collection of
agencies for Whitehall administering nationally funded services.
In Britain we are too afraid of pluralist decision-making, of the
complexities created by recognising the rights of representation, democratic
accountability and open government. But the dangers of disenfranchisement
are greater, and all Londoners will be the worse for it.
Julie Fitzgerald,
leader,
London borough of Camden,
Euston Road, London NW1 2RU
</TEXT>
<XX>
