<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Letter: Success of warehouse clubs in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JIM LOWE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The fundamental success of the warehouse clubs in the US is based on a
number of key factors ('Superstores under threat', March 24). They have
hypermarket-type advantages of scale and cost efficiencies. They have the
unique advantage of mixing trade (wholesale) and consumer retail sales. With
very high labour productivity and cheap rents, the clubs can afford to live
on 10 to 12 per cent gross margins.
The clubs are a type of larger second-generation out-of-town Kwik Save or
Aldi, with a wider range of foods and non-foods. Their ultimate strength is
more as a retail discounter than a wholesaler. Their competitive positioning
in the UK, assuming retail planning consents, is more a threat to retail
superstores/discounters than to cash-and-carry wholesaling.
The UK cash-and-carry sector, carrying a very full (rather than limited)
food range, can operate on 5 to 7 per cent gross margins and is already on
best or near-best supplier buying terms. Clubs needing more margin will not
always stock brand leaders, and will not initially have a UK critical mass
of buying power. On a straight retail discount basis, the estimate of 30
units in 10 years can be multiplied by at least a factor of two.
Jim Lowe,
JL Consultants,
18 Regent Road,
Altrincham, Cheshire
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
