<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Book Review: Voice of warning in Russia's power play
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW GOWERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STRUGGLE FOR RUSSIA
Power and Change in the Democratic Revolution
By Ruslan Khasbulatov, edited by Richard Sakwa
Routledge, Pounds 19.99, 270 pages
In the theatre of the absurd that passes for Russian politics these days, no
actor cuts a figure as surreal or paradoxical as parliamentary speaker
Ruslan Khasbulatov.
Stalwart defender of the constitutional order against totalitarian threats,
or demagogic standard-bearer of the old communist guard? Dangerous
reactionary bent on sabotaging reform and unseating the president, or
pragmatic coalition-builder groping for a consensual way out of Russia's
multiple crises? At various times during the session of the Congress of
People's Deputies that ended in confusion on Monday, Khasbulatov was accused
of playing all these roles. And while he emerged claiming victory over
Yeltsin, this was only after the speaker had survived a serious attempt in
Congress to dismiss him.
This book - a mixture of personal memoir and political and economic musings
put together over the past 18 months - is Khasbulatov's first attempt to
explain himself to an English-speaking public. As such its publication could
hardly be more timely. Stodgily written and sometimes less than clear, it
does create a more rounded picture of the man than has hitherto been
available. But it also serves to deepen the confusion surrounding the Moscow
power struggle in which he has, for now at least, become a central player.
Are he and the forces he claims to represent really the nub of President
Yeltsin's political problem, to be wished away through a popular vote of
confidence on April 25? Or are they likely to prove an essential part of any
constitutional solution? The question has posed itself insistently in the 15
months since Khasbulatov's Congress started to challenge Yeltsin's
government and its economic reforms. And it is one to which Yeltsin himself
still appears unsure of the answer, even as he prepares to do open battle
with parliament for public support.
What does emerge clearly enough from these pages is that the image of
Khasbulatov which Yeltsin and his supporters have painted in their more
headstrong moments is a caricature. The parliament speaker may be a
political opportunist but he is not exactly a Stalinist of the old school,
yearning for restoration of the centralised Soviet state and actively
plotting with other members of the nomenklatura to achieve it.
True, he is a product of the communist career ladder: from his birth as an
ethnic Chechen in the town of Grozny and his childhood in forced exile in
Kazakhstan, making his way up through the Komsomol youth organisation and
into academe before being elected - a communist like 80 per cent of his
peers - a people's deputy in Russia's almost-democratic parliament in March
1990.
But then Yeltsin himself occupied numerous powerful party positions before
setting out on his own political trajectory. Indeed, for more than a year
Yeltsin and Khasbulatov were comrades in arms. They served together as
parliament speaker and deputy speaker respectively from May 1990. They both
pushed the cause of economic reform as Gorbachev's central government
vacillated with its 500-day plan and then drifted to the right. Most
important, after Yeltsin had been elected Russian president and Khasbulatov
had taken over as speaker, they both manned the barricades and drafted the
decrees at Moscow's White House during the August 1991 coup - a lively if
somewhat sketchy account of which forms the central section of this volume.
Such close collaboration between the two men in the past makes their more
recent falling-out seem especially bitter. Khasbulatov does not dwell on the
personal aspect of their current struggle, but some of his asides betray
pique at the fact that the solidarity they displayed during the coup did not
long survive it. 'Unfortunately, we placed too much faith immediately after
the suppression of the coup on the president and his team,' he writes
ruefully. Behind his animus towards those he calls Yeltsin's 'latter-day
courtiers', however, lies a multitude of real differences on subjects
ranging from the pace of economic reform to the structure of government and
the devolution of powers from the centre to Russia's regions.
Khasbulatov, a lawyer and economics professor, presents at least a plausible
diagnosis of Russia's problems. In the political as well as the economic
sphere, he argues, the collapse of the old system means the executive has
lost the capacity to govern. 'The pyramid of power controlled by the state
party was a terrible thing,' he writes without obvious nostalgia. 'But one
way or another it managed to govern. Having broken the hundred thousand or
so links of this mechanism's chain, from the Central Committee to the
district committee, from the factory to the collective farm, what did we put
in its place?'
For Khasbulatov, that question - what to put in its place - defines the
battle for Russia's future. Yeltsin's reformers want to break the chain
further, privatise faster, accelerate the disposal of state mono-liths to
the point where a restoration of central control becomes inconceivable. The
speaker would reply that this way chaos lies - the government cannot hope to
impose reform without the co-operation of Russia's real centres of economic
power such as state industry. That means seeking to involve the parliament,
which represents such interests, not bypassing it - and creating a system of
government with a proper separation and devolution of powers.
Is Russia to have reform by diktat or reform by consent? More to the point,
can either succeed while such fundamental political issues are in dispute?
The dilemmas have been too frequently oversimplified of late as western
governments have leapt unhesitatingly to Yeltsin's side. Khasbulatov's book
is a useful, and pretty depressing, counterblast.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-17351</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDACLAD2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930401
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Economic Viewpoint: Difficult to lock in low inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last time UK inflation was low - in the mid-1980s - there was discussion
of how to 'lock in' that low rate, which obviously owed something to
temporary factors. The obvious suggestion then was to tie sterling to the
low-inflation D-Mark via the European exchange rate mechanism.
The indications, which I discussed in this column last week, of a possible
change in the long-range world economic climate from inflation to deflation
increase the need for the UK to try to lock itself in on this occasion. It
was none other than Harold MacMillan who warned of the follies of being 'an
island of inflation in a sea of deflation'.
What are the prospects? Both headline and underlying rates of UK inflation
fell last autumn and winter much further than generally realised. The annual
increase in the retail prices index, excluding mortgage payments, was 3.4
per cent in February - up 0.2 of a percentage point compared with the
January figure, but still lower than in any year since the 1960s. Non-food
producer prices rose only 2.7 per cent in the year to February.
The best anti-inflationary news is on the labour front. The annual rise in
earnings per head is now down to 4 3/4 per cent, compared with a minimum of
7 1/2 per cent in the 1980s. Meanwhile manufacturing productivity has been
increasing at 5 1/2 to 6 per cent a year - remarkably rapidly for the late
stages of a recession or the early stages of a recovery. Right-wing Tories,
who are the government's real opposition, only show their own innumeracy
when they say the gains of the Thatcher years have been either thrown away
or proved a snare and a delusion.
In any case the combination of wage moderation and productivity rise has led
to a slight fall in manufacturing unit wage costs. It is this measure which
has some claim to be the best one of the domestically generated core rate of
inflation.
The present phase, however, owes a lot to exceptional circumstances: namely
the pressure on British costs imposed by two years in the ERM at a
'challenging' exchange rate, combined with a severe domestic recession.
Since last autumn's 15 per cent effective devaluation of sterling, prices
connected with imports have been rising. Materials and fuels purchased by
manufacturing industry have risen by 7 per cent in a mere six months on a
seasonally adjusted basis. The devaluation occurred at the best possible
time in the cycle, when market forces were restraining the extent of
pass-through. But there is no way a depreciation of this size can fail to
affect recorded inflation.
Thus inflation indices have climbed back a little above their recent low
point; and the Treasury expects RPI inflation, excluding mortgage interest
rates, to bounce back to 3 3/4 per cent by the end of the year, while the
chancellor's independent experts expect 4 per cent.
The government naturally hopes the bounce-back will be temporary and the
devaluation effects 'once for all', passing away like clouds over a summer
landscape. This would allow inflation to settle down towards the bottom end
of the chancellor's 1 to 4 per cent target range.
What do the financial markets expect? Fortunately the existence of
index-linked gilt-edged securities gives some insight into the inflationary
expectations. Take a 10-year gilt-edged security with a gross redemption
yield of about 7.8 per cent a year. Then subtract from it the yield on an
indexed gilt of comparable maturity of 3.4 per cent. The difference is an
approximation to the expected average annual inflation rate over the next
year which comes out at about 4.4 per cent. This dodges the influence of
tax. But, as Maurice Scott argues in the February National Institute Review,
it is likely that tax-exempt pension funds and charities dominate the
index-linked market.
The details of how we reached the current position are interesting. During
previous periods of comparatively low inflationary expectations, normal
gilt-edged yields have come down. This pattern has been paralleled on the
present occasion by an only slightly smaller fall in the yield on indexed
gilts themselves.
Indexed-linked securities are a rarity outside the UK. But the fall in
yields on ordinary nominal British government securities has been echoed in
so many other countries in such different circumstances, that it is
difficult to believe that the driving force is only inflationary
expectations. There has probably been a drop in real interest rates in the
main industrial countries of about a percentage point to, say, 3 1/2 per
cent. You can ascribe this to the prolongation of the world recession. Or
you can say that the expected 'world shortage of capital' has failed to
materialise, as the needs for investment of the former communist countries
and others have not been accompanied by an effective demand for funds on
terms attractive to western investors.
The UK departure from the ERM did worsen expectations of future UK
short-term nominal interest rates. The chart of expected one-year interest
rates, derived by the Bank of England from the structure of gilt-edged
yields, rose in one week last September by more than one percentage point.
Since then, expected rates for a couple of years ahead have fallen
drastically in line with actual experience. But several years out they have
not recovered from Black Wednesday.
The other small chart shows that for a couple of years ahead there is little
difference between expected one-year interest rates in the UK and Germany.
But as one looks further ahead, expected UK interest rates climb back to
nearly 10 per cent, some 2 percentage points higher than anything expected
in Germany.
Financial markets are not predicting inflationary catastrophes. But they
know that governments are tempted to expand the economy too far as an
election approaches and thus sacrifice hard won inflationary gains.
The textbook remedy is that a government should tie its own hands,
'pre-commit itself', or something of that kind. There are only a limited
number of ways in which this can be done.
One example would have been a fixed-rate regime such as the ERM, which the
government could not abandon without losing a lot of political face. Another
would be to distance itself by means of an independent Bank of England.
Unfortunately credibility has been so badly damaged by the manner of
Britain's exit from the ERM that simply to rejoin it at some future time
would not be sufficient to rebuild credibility.
The Bank of England has made too much of Chancellor Norman Lamont's
published statement to the new governor, Eddie George, on his appointment
that 'his central responsibility should be to support the government in our
determination to bring about a lasting reduction in the rate of inflation,
the only sound basis on which sustainable growth and secure jobs can be
built'. This statement still leaves the government with the last word.
Indeed to rebuild credibility now requires belt, braces and suspenders. This
means a genuinely independent Bank of England and the return to a European
monetary arrangement as soon as conditions permit. Both would be achieved
together if the British government would co-operate with the new French
government in an attempt to make a real go of European monetary union. I
know the political obstacles and John Major and the Conservative whips could
name them all one by one.
 -------------------------------------------
INFLATION IN THE G7
 -------------------------------------------
