<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Arts: Barstow's 'Fidelio' - Opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The latest run of Fidelio performances at Covent Garden brings Josephine
Barstow to the title role. This immediately raises the production (first
seen in 1990, first revived last September) on to a higher plane of dramatic
vitality than it has so far reached. There are, however, still higher ones
yet to be attained. Though now shorn of those dreadful passages of
re-written dialogue inserted by the original producer, Adolf Dresen, the
staging remains limp and lacklustre - purposelessly fussy in domestic
scenes, hovering on the edge of comical ineptitude in the finale.
And withal Miss Barstow, taut in bearing, intent in every glance and
gesture, anchors the opera in dramatic credibility in spite of every passing
threat thereto. On the most basic level, as Tuesday's performance showed,
she remains physically the most credible of boy-girls - tall, coltish, made
scrawny by desperation and determination. Beyond this, she carries within
her that essential set-apart-ness which not only proves attractive to
Marzelline and plausible to Rocco but chimes with the character's effect on
Beethoven's musical development of the opera.
There are, I know, those pitiable souls unresponsive to the controlled
magnetism of the Barstow stage presence, alienated by the intense,
complicated quality of vocal timbre and not compensated by the fiery
musicianship that underlies it. This singer has always struggled with
Leonore's music (but few indeed are those who have not]), yet it seems to me
that she now deals with it far more fluently than in those Glyndebourne and
ENO Fidelios more than a decade ago.
To the doubters I would simply reply by first affirming that this is of
course not the gloriously outpouring Heldensopran Leonore of legend; and by
then insisting that it is an achievement all the more remarkable, more
meaningful, for that.
Other valuable elements abound in the revival: once they have come together
more cohesively, a Fidelio of real ensemble character is in prospect. The
young couple, Gillian Webster and Lynton Atkinson, are appealing; there is
an absolutely first-rate Rocco - robust, bluff, calculating and craven all
at one go - from the Austrian bass Kurt Rydl (house debut), whose only
misjudgment is an excess of loud singing.
Reiner Goldberg's Florestan, substituted at short notice for Josef
Protschka's, is reedy, edgy, affecting. While Willard White, warm-toned and
innately noble in stage personality, may not seem obvious casting for
Pizarro, his performance certainly registers. Jeffrey Tate conducts - not
always precisely, but with energy (apart from a couple of slack tempos in
Act 2), dramatic sensitivity, a winning altertness to the specific musical
workings of every page and passage.
Royal Opera House: in repertory until April 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
