<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Arts: Artist's block - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE QUINCE TREE SUN (U)
Victor Erice
THE SILENT TOUCH (15)
Krzysztof Zanussi
USED PEOPLE (12)
Beeban Kidron
NIGHT OF THE LIVING DEAD (18)
Tom Savini
SPLITTING HEIRS (12)
Robert Young
MR NANNY (PG)
Michael Gottlieb
Artists are funny people. Put a pen or brush in their hands and they either
bend to their task with monkish devotion (painter Antonio Lopez in Victor
Erice's The Quince Tree Sun) or throw tantrums, empty whisky bottles and
impregnate their secretaries (composer Max Von Sydow in Krzysztof Zanussi's
The Silent Touch).
Of the two options, neither guarantees a good time for the spectator. But of
the two films both have major curiosity value. Erice's is a Spanish TV
documentary that sprouted wings and became a Cannes prize-winning feature.
And Zanussi's is a Euro-pudding that plunges earthward only after some
fiery, spirit-soaked mumming from Von Sydow.
The star of The Quince Tree Sun is the quince tree. Standing in the dusty
backyard of Senor Lopez, a real Madrid artist, it beckons his paintbrush.
For 2 1/4 hours we watch him fail to complete the canvas that is his main
work one wet autumn. Though rain stops paint, it does not deter the film's
sense of near-religious eventlessness. Lopez lives on bread, air and the odd
glass of Spanish plonk. In and out of his life wander a dog, a wife, two
daughters, a painter friend and a Chinese visitor. And there are shots of
nearby apartment-block windows, of a rail-line, of Mrs Lopez pottering or
herself painting. She is working on a picture of Mr Lopez prone on a bed,
his sole recreation away from the quince tree.
The film is fascinating: but not for the reason its admirers proclaim. They
see an affirmative fable of spiritual and artistic struggle as the
film-maker watches the painter work out his subject. Lopez suspends
plumblines and paints white check-marks on the leaves to ensure the
consistency of the image in face of the capriciousness of Nature.
But I am not in the uplifting masterpiece camp. The film fascinates because
it embodies the struggle it depicts: it has Nothing To Say and yet says it
with a crazed, anomic majesty. Erice is no stranger to minimalism. But where
his first film The Spirit Of The Beehive was about the mysteries of growing
up in a world of opaque and sinister mysticism - it had a sense of progress,
however pained and slow - The Quince Tree Sun is a cinematic cul-de-sac
pretending to be a through-road. An absurd artistic task - who needs
mathematical pictures of fruit trees? - is absurdly apotheosised, right up
to its absurd quietus. The occasional spurt of beauty or serendipitous
insight makes the experience more poignant, more tantalising. For
inspiration under siege is both the subject of The Quince Tree Sun and the
style of its making.
It is also the reason we are drawn to Max Von Sydow's crusty Danish composer
in The Silent Touch. Wrestling with an uncompliant muse, the only notes
Sydow has composed in 40 years are to the milkman. Now he lives in a country
mansion with wife Sarah Miles. He is a moody mage wrapped in winter rugs
until Polish student Lothaire Bluteau (Jesus of Montreal) bursts into their
peace. Bluteau can water-divine; he can heal by the 'silent touch' of hands;
and he can re-animate, he claims, Von S's creative juices.
Polish director Krzysztof Zanussi has dealt before - and better - with the
self-destruct energies of the human mind and imagination. See Illumination
and Camouflage. For The Silent Touch, first fruit of a new European
Co-production Fund, his original story idea has been hijacked by two English
writers, Peter Morgan and Mark Wadlow. A tale that should fly through
strange high-altitude corridors known only to KZ is instead forced to make
for Banality Airport, where everybody speaks the same language
(Euro-English) and stars from different countries can gather in the VIP
lounge.
When not enacting the timeless drama of the Impossible Genius - Von Sydow
beds everything on two legs, including his nubile new secretary, and breaks
everything else - the film plods through its over-schemed, quasi-Faustian
transference-of-creativity scenario between student and genius.
The confrontations are stagey and the dialogue is by hot-air speech balloon.
Thank heaven then for Mad Max. The Swedish actor chews his role as if it
were the sourest Hesperidean apple. At times he spits out bits he does not
like; at others he fills his mouth with noises of pagan, guttural relish. If
we must have the art movie as Euro-bathos, let us at least have a Euro-star
making a meal of things at the centre.
*****
The giant moon that hovered over Moonstruck has been re-hired for Used
People. Its presence indicates that rooftop yearnings from New York's ethnic
community will loom large and so will bitter-sweet melancholy. 'Life's
tough, so laugh a little' insists the moon-bathed poster. So we do: at this
likable, oldfashioned, sentimental - let us face it, creaky - comedy about
second-chancers.
Second-chancers are mature people who, cheated by life to date, suddenly
turn around and order life to pay recompense. Thus Shirley MacLaine, a
sixtyish Jewish widow from Queens who has spent too long washing dishes and
raising children, accepts it when Marcello Mastroianni, an Italian roue
dressed in 1930s-era 'Anyone for Venice' clothes, kindles the first spark of
romance at her husband's funeral party.
Self-liberation soon spreads virus-like through the family. Homebound
grandma Jessica Tandy just might buzz off to Florida with best friend Sylvia
Sidney. And MacLaine's daughters, frumpish Kathy Bates and neurotic beauty
Marcia Gay Harden (her young son already a psychiatric couch-case), just
might make a respective dash for glamour and responsible motherhood.
Todd Graff's screenplay spreads in all directions like an overturned syrup
tin. But British director Beeban Kidron (of TV's Oranges Are Not The Only
Fruit) moves essential household objects into position - spaghetti pans,
double-beds, televisions broadcasting the first moon landing - to corral the
schmaltz. A wry, gawky domestic everydayness stands guard over the
escape-prone whimsy. So does a first-class cast. Invidious to pick out one
member, so I will. Shirley MacLaine: for crackerjack acting and for having
the nerve to look 60, at least until her wedding day when the make-up men
hitch up her cheeks and cameraman David Watkin puts about 28 gauzes (my
count) between her and the softly focused camera.
In Night Of The Living Dead no one gets the soft-focus treatment. Worse, a
professional make-up man has escaped and is running amok across the country.
George Romero's 1968 zombie classic is here remade in colour by Tom Savini,
cosmetician on the earlier film.
Savini shreds our nerves with a razor-sharp replay of Romero's opening
scene: the graveyard ghouls lumbering forth in broad daylight to terrify the
heroine and KO her brother. Then the film battles bravely against dwindling
returns, as we movie into the all-colour bloodbath in the zombie-besieged
farmhouse. Savini's hopping camera and Romero's own no-nonsense script
ensure few lulls in energy. But menace is a more elusive matter. The
black-and-white original - perhaps by being black and white - had menace
galore.
Splitting Heirs and Mr Nanny fight it out for the Week's Worst Comedy award.
Before we open the envelope, let us have a sample scene from each. Here in
Splitting Heirs, directed by Robert Young, we see writer-star Eric Idle drop
his trousers, fall over, bump into John Cleese, disappear down Barbara
Hershey's cleavage and discover he is a British aristocrat not an
Anglo-Indian Hindu investment broker. (Short pause for polite laughter). And
in our scene from Mr Nanny, directed by Michael Gottlieb, wrestler-star Hulk
Hogan dons a tutu, biffs a visiting party of gangsters, saves the children
he is bodyguarding, rips off Home Alone and falls into a pond. (Same).
And the winner is . . .
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
