<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With television, more even than most areas of life, nothing succeeds like
success: appear on one chat show and you will promptly be invited on to
others; star in a successful series and you will be wooed by every breakfast
programme and game show on every channel. Flavour of the year so far has
been Richard Wilson who plays the misanthropic Victor Meldrew in 'One Foot
In The Grave'. Today BBC2 shows Richard Wilson: A Life Beyond The Grave
(8.00) in which he travels back to his home town of Greenock and colleagues
assess his talents. The current run of Minder, not the best ever but not the
worst, either, ends with Arthur and Ray in Australia trying to raise the
readies to get back to London (8.30 ITV). French &amp; Saunders ends with a
parody of 'Thelma and Louise' (9.00 BBC2) and the archive series A Labour Of
Love, about child care in Britain between 1900 and 1950, finishes with a
look at nannies and foster mothers (9.30 BBC2). BBC1's series on
miscarriages of justice, Rough Justice, investigates the case of Patrick
Kane who was given a life sentence after two British soldiers were stripped
and shot by the IRA (9.30).
</TEXT>
