<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Caring for key
clients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How much emphasis should companies place on managing their key customers?
The question was tackled - if not necessarily resolved - this week at a
seminar organised by the Sundridge Park corporate and executive development
centre in Kent.
Top of the agenda were results from what Sundridge Park believes is the
first reliable UK survey of Account Management (shorthand for the art of
paying particular attention to, and developing a long-term relationship
with, specific customers). Based on the responses from 300 manufacturing and
service businesses, the survey demonstrates that practice for the moment
varies widely: in 18-19 per cent of companies polled, for example, more than
four fifths of total turnover is handled by account managers, but in nearly
25 per cent of cases the figure drops to under a fifth of total sales.
Among the findings is evidence that too much may be expected of account
managers - on average individuals in half the companies looked after more
than six clients, which some experts think may be too much.
Training needs are also being neglected - 40 per cent of companies said
there had been no formal training for account managers in the last year. Nor
are the rewards exactly handsome. Two thirds of respondent companies were
paying under Pounds 30,000 (including commissions and bonus) per manager,
and 16 per cent less than Pounds 20,000.
More encouragingly, there are signs that companies have been able to
integrate account management across product areas and different territories
The most important test, of course, is the bottom line. Sundridge detects a
tentative link between 'defensive' or 'responsive' sales strategies and
lower sales growth. But more research is needed to establish a clearer
relationship between offensive strategies such as account management and
better performance.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7311 Advertising Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
