<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Commons approves legal aid
restriction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs last night approved new regulations restricting eligibility for legal
aid, and rejected alternative proposals by the Law Society.
The regulations, which take effect from April 12, were approved by a
government majority of 45 (304-259).
But the measures were attacked by Labour and Liberal Democrat MPs and by Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn (C Perth and Kinross), a former solicitor-general for
Scotland.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, the junior Scottish office minister, promised
that the regulations would be reviewed in due course, but said: 'I cannot
hold out any hope with regard to the representations by the Law Society'.
Responding to protests that people with modest resources unable to qualify
for income support would be hardest hit by the regulations, he said such
complaints would be made wherever the line restricting eligibility was
drawn.
The minister emphasised the escalation in the cost of legal aid throughout
Britain - on current trends estimated to reach Pounds 2bn by 1995-96 - and
insisted 'something had to be done'.
Pointing out that it was envisaged that legal aid expenditure would rise by
10 per cent a year for the next three years he said Lord Mackay, the Lord
Chancellor, had not been 'ungenerous' in framing the regulations.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton forecast that the numbers receiving legal aid
would increase steadily by the mid-1990s.
Sir Ivan Lawrence QC (C Burton), chairman of the Commons home affairs
committee, denied that 14m people would be denied legal aid as a result of
the regulations.
He joined other MPs in calling for reforms in the administration of the
courts to provide greater value for money.
</TEXT>
