<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Security service cleared on phone
taps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE security service has been cleared of installing bugging devices or
tapping telephones unlawfully, by the two judges who scrutinise its work,
Alison Smith writes.
Sir Thomas Bingham, the commissioner who reviews intercepting
communications, and Lord Hustice Stuart-Smith, the commissioner who reviews
the security service, both use their annual reports to express confidence
the service is not acting illegally.
The assurances do not refer to specific incidents, but are clearly directed
at rumours that the so-called 'Squidgy' and 'Camillagate' tapes, allegedly
recordings of a telephone conversations between members of the royal family
and friends, had originated within the security service.
Commenting on newspaper reports of eavesdropping operations, Sir Thomas
said: 'Such stories are, in my experience without exception, false. They
give . . an entirely misleading impression both of the extent of official
interception and of the targets against which interception is directed'.
Lord Justice Stuart-Smith said he based his opinion on the tight control
within the system and the fact that operations were so complex that
resources were unlikely to be squandered on them and they would be hard to
conceal.
</TEXT>
