<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Law Lords put Sunday trading in
doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities were yesterday given the power to clamp down on shops that
open on Sundays, after the Law Lords dismissed an appeal by B&amp;Q, the DIY
chain, ending its five-year legal battle over Sunday trading laws in England
and Wales.
Opponents of Sunday opening urged councils to use their powers, but
retailers already trading on Sundays vowed to continue. They said they would
intensify pressure on the government to introduce new legislation to replace
the 1950 Shops Act, widely seen as impractical and outdated.
The Law Lords said that following a European Court judgment in December it
was clear that European rules, which prohibited quantitative restrictions on
trade between EC states, did not apply to national legislation prohibiting
retailers from opening their premises on Sundays.
B&amp;Q had argued that the ban on Sunday opening was incompatible with
free-trade principles of the European Community. This argument was rejected
by Mr Justice Hoffmann in a 1990 ruling. The DIY chain appealed to the Law
Lords who referred the issue to the European Court for the second time since
1988.
Giving judgment yesterday, Lord Goff said the European Court's second answer
was so 'unequivocal' that B&amp;Q's appeal must fail.
The Shopping Hours Reform Council, which is calling for partial deregulation
of Sunday opening, said the ruling cleared the way for the government to
bring forward its proposals for new legislation.
'Shoppers, shopworkers and shopkeepers will all raise three cheers if the
government gets a move on,' the council said.
Keep Sunday Special, the campaign group which supports only restricted
Sunday opening, agreed on the need for reform. But Dr Michael Schluter,
campaign director, said it was 'totally unacceptable for the multiples to
flout existing Sunday trading law.
Mr Bill Connor, deputy general secretary of Usdaw, the shopworkers' union,
agreed there was 'no longer any excuse' for retailers to disobey the law.
Dr Schluter added that an opportunity for reform already existed in the
private member's bill introduced by Mr Ray Powell, Labour MP for Ogmore, due
to begin its report stage on May 14. However, the bill, based broadly on the
Keep Sunday Special's proposals, is unlikely to become law, and opponents
say it is riddled with anomalies.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, last week promised a draft bill to
reform the Sunday trading laws would be published within the next few
months, together with a paper about its impact.
Among retailers, Mr George Robertson, Sainsbury's senior legal adviser, said
the Lords' ruling would not affect its plans to open on Sundays.
Sainsbury's is trying to persuade local authorities to use their powers
under Section 48 of the Shops Act to make exemption orders allowing grocery
shops to open between 10am and 4pm if a majority of local retailers is in
favour.
Tesco also pledged to continue opening, while Safeway said it had no
intention of disappointing its shoppers. But Marks and Spencer and John
Lewis Partnership said they would continue to uphold the law and not open on
Sundays.
Only a handful of councils, including Kirklees (which has been in dispute
with Tesco), Norwich, Stoke, Torfaen and The Wrekin, have continued to
enforce Sunday trading laws, but others, including Waverley, Horsham,
Ashford, Kennet, Cambridge, and Wyre Forest, have indicated they would seek
prosecutions or injunctions if the House of Lords upheld the European Court
ruling. Opponents of Sunday shopping believe at least 20 others may follow
suit.
</TEXT>
<XX>
