<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Corporate operators ready to take a slice of the caring
market: Today sees the implementation of the government's care in the
community initiative which moves the onus on to local councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARING for people is set to become a serious business sector with large
operators moving in to challenge small providers - as long as there is
enough finance to make it profitable.
The reforms are designed to create a 'mixed economy' in care, with local
authorities purchasing services but contracting out delivery to the private
and voluntary sec-tors.
Local authorities will be required to spend 85 per cent of social security
transfer funds - about two thirds of their total care in the community
grants - in the independent sector. That will not be hard,since local
authorities provide only a minority of places in homes. But there will be a
battle royal between competing providers for the new business.
The residential care market is something of a cottage industry, with large
numbers of small, owner-managed homes. But there is growing activity by big
corporate providers such as Takare, Westminster Health Care, Crestacare and
Ashbourne Homes, and from voluntary sector providers such as the Anchor
Housing Association and the Abbeyfield Society.
As the reforms reduce the flow of people entering residential care the
smaller homes will come under increasing pressure from corporate operators.
Mr Keith Bradshaw, chairman of Takare - the biggest corporate provider,
still with only about 2 per cent of the market - believes many smaller homes
are not economically viable.
Many local authorities have hived off their own former homes into trusts
which will count as part of the independent sector for financing purposes.
The private sector suspects it may face unfair competition from these and
from National Health Service community services trusts, which will also be
regarded as independent providers.
The private sector is far less developed in day care and home care - which
is where growth will be. Here, initially at least, the voluntary
organisations will make the running. Today's reforms provide the biggest
opportunity yet to bring a fundamental policy shift in provision of welfare
services from public authorities to the voluntary sector.
Some household name charities are likely to become very large welfare
service organisations as a result of the reforms. The British Red Cross and
Age Concern are setting up central contracts units to support branches in
negotiations with local authorities. Even so, the voluntary sector still has
worries.
Some fear loss of independence and campaigning power if charities become too
dependent on public-sector contracts. Others fear that local authorities
will not pay an economic price for charities' services.
Many charities have had to cost their services for the first time - and
concluded that in the past they were receiving far too little in public
grants. Age Concern has expressed 'grave anxiety' about charities
subsidising public services to the detriment of other activities, stressing
that local authorities should pay an economic price for services purchased
from charities.
The private sector has similar concerns about the rates local authorities
will pay for services such home helps - unglamorous activity, but vital if
the objective of helping dependent people stay in their own homes is to be
achieved.
Ms Lucianne Sawyer, who runs Care Alternatives, a non-profitmaking
organisation in London, and is president of the UK Home Care Association,
says: 'It really doesn't make much difference whether you are a profitmaking
organisation or not, because there is so little profit there. Maintaining
quality is essential, and we insist on high standards from association
members. But they are competing with people who puts cards in newsagents'
windows. Home care will not work if it is regarded as a cheaper alternative
to residential care.'
The care in the community reforms are also being watched with keen interest
by the insurance industry. Long-term care insurance is a recent innovation
in the UK market, but since 1991 policies have been available providing
residential and home care benefits.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE BIG COMPANY. . .
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Takare
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Largest private-sector provider of nursing home care with 2 per cent of
  the market
Stock market capitalisation pounds 217.6m
1992 turnover pounds 48m, pre-tax profit pounds 11.8m
No. of beds 4,785. Occupancy rate 98 per cent
Mr Keith Bradshaw, chief executive, says: 'On balance I believe the care
  in the community reforms to be well conceived. I am optimistic it will
  work to the benefit of both of our residents and Takare.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SMALL COMPANY. . .
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
York Helpers, Nannies and Nurses
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Typical of the type of company local authorities will involve in the
  provision of home-based care under the reforms
Set up by Ms Juliet Agnew in 1984. About 125 carers on its books
Ms Agnew says: 'I think the move to the mixed economy in care is going
  to a gradual one. Much will depend on finance, including some people
  discovering they have to pay for services that may have been free in
  the past.'
