<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Things will never be the same again: For better or for
worse, today, April Fool's Day, sees the launch of a range of measures from
care in the community to council tax. FT reporters pick out some of the
fresh starts in the private and the public sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FT Reporters
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE APRIL 1 change that will affect most people is the replacement of the
poll tax by the council tax.
The council tax has won more general acceptance than the poll tax, which
prompted rioting on the streets and resignations among Tory councillors and
contributed to Mrs Thatcher's downfall. The change returns local taxation to
a property base, loosely relating it to ability to pay. The task of putting
every home into one of eight valuation bands was completed late last year,
but only from today can a householder appeal against the ruling.
The government has provided for up to 1m appeals. Anecdotal evidence
suggests that there will be many appeals to move down to a cheaper band, but
some people may appeal to move up a band in the belief that the suggestion
of a higher house value is worth a small rise in tax.
The bill for a two-person household in a band C (Pounds 52,000-68,000) home
varies from Pounds 704 in Newcastle upon Tyne to Pounds 218 in
Wellingborough, Northamptonshire.
Unemployment: Many unemployed people will be affected by today's launch of
the Training for Work scheme, which combines Employment Training, the main
training scheme for the adult jobless, with Employment Action, the work
experience scheme.
At any time there will be 150,000 people on the scheme, with about 320,000
opportunities in any year. It has a budget of Pounds 936m in 1993-94 -
Pounds 40m less than spending on ET and EA this year - and cuts training
from 26 weeks to 14 weeks.
Homelessness: For the homeless in central London today is the first day
without their nine winter shelters, closed yesterday.
The Pounds 1.5m programme to help people sleeping rough had provided 400
extra bed spaces in the shelters. Mr Tony Baldry, junior environment
minister, said those still using them would be found alternative
accommodation.
Business: West Yorkshire's main business communities of Leeds and Bradford
today partially bury their old rivalry by merging most functions of their
chambers of commerce and industry. Each will continue to represent business
in its area, but services will be run by a joint company, with equal numbers
of directors from Leeds and Bradford.
Its offices are likely to be in Pudsey, which is officially in Leeds, and
has a Leeds postcode, but parts of it have Bradford telephone numbers.
Coal: Contracts by which British Coal will sell coal worth Pounds 5.5bn to
the electricity generators over five years and provide a future for 19 mines
 -12 reprieved, six mothballed and one to be developed - take effect today
following months of wrangling over the contracts which were finally signed
earlier this week.
The protracted wrangling was one reason why last week's coal white paper was
not able to guarantee a future for a further 19 mines which have been
reprieved or mothballed.
Uncertainty over their fate will continue while British Coal negotiates
additional contracts with the generators. The generators have contracted to
sell the power produced to the regional electricity companies for about
Pounds 13bn.
Health: A total of 132 National Health Service hospitals, community services
and ambulance services become trusts managing their own day-to-day affairs.
It is the third wave since the launch of the government's health reforms in
1991. When a fourth wave comes on stream next April almost all hospital and
community services will be delivered by locally managed trusts.
Army: The army's new baby is the Royal Logistic Corps, formed from the Royal
Corps of Transport, the Royal Army Ordnance Corps, the Royal Pioneer Corps,
the Army Catering Corps and the postal and courier services of the Royal
Engineers.
BBC: Not everyone at the corporation is laughing on April Fool's Day, which
sees the start of Producer Choice - the system which will give producers
full control of their budgets. Many people are expected to lose their jobs
in the process.
Humour: Appropriately, April 1 sees the launch of The Cartoonist, a
fortnightly newspaper devoted to cartoons.
The publication, which costs Pounds 1.20, will follow the format of a
national newspaper with cartoons on politics and current events in the front
half and sports at the back.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
