<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Councils doubt adequacy of age funding provisions: Today
sees the implementation of the government's care in the community initiative
which moves the onus on to local councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW POLICY changes have been heralded with a more potent cocktail of
goodwill and doubt than today's care in the community reforms.
Politicians of all parties, doctors and social workers applaud the central
objective - to care for elderly and handicapped people in the community
rather than in institutions. That is the goodwill. The doubt arises over
finance.
One of the political objectives of the reforms is to end a bias in public
funding arrangements that has encouraged the growth of residential care
because social security benefits have been available to pay for it. From
today local authority social services departments will be responsible for
deciding how individuals' needs should be met, either in residential care or
at home.
The previous system was demand-led - people who qualified for social
security support could use their entitlement like a residential care voucher
when looking for a home. The system's replacement will be cash-limited
within the overall local government financing structure.
In 1993-94, Pounds 399m will be transferred from the social security budget
to local authorities - based on calculations of the number of new residents
who would have entered homes this year had the old system continued - plus
an additional Pounds 140m in start-up costs. The social security transfers
will rise to Pounds 1.05bn in 1994-95 and Pounds 1.56bn in 1995-96.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, squeezed more money from the
Treasury than her critics expected in the current difficult public spending
climate. Doubts still remain about whether the money is enough.
The Commons health committee said last month that its efforts to judge the
adequacy of funding had been 'hampered by a lack of transparency about the
assumptions used by the Department of Health'. Some local authorities
believe the government had under-estimated the number of people who would
have entered homes this year under the old system.
People living in homes before today's changes are excluded from the new
arrangements, but many already suffer from a shortfall between levels of
social security payment and residential home fees. Ministers hope local
authorities will use their bargaining muscle as bulk purchasers of
residential care to drive prices down. Some local authority leaders and home
operators are not as optimistic.
Mr David Wigley, chief executive of Methodist Homes, one of the biggest
charitable residential care providers, says his charity already spends
Pounds 400,000 a year subsidising social security-financed residents in its
homes. A Methodist Homes' survey of 41 English and Welsh local authorities
revealed that more than one third would limit expenditure on residential
care under the new system to social security levels.
For elderly people without personal resources, the gap between income
support and home fees is sometimes met by relatives. Others depend on
charities, but a number of these are withdrawing from topping-up payments.
Mr Geoff Smith, general manager of the charity Counsel and Care for the
Elderly, says: 'We will meet existing commitments, but have concluded that
it is not an appropriate use of charitable funds to subsidise the social
security system. The reforms will not work properly unless they are
adequately funded. But the problem is that inadequate funding will not
necessarily show in a coherent way. Poverty often just disappears into
individual misery.'
</TEXT>
