<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Sharp rise seen in orders for manufacturers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH manufacturing industry is experiencing 'considerable growth' of
output and orders, the latest monthly survey of UK purchasing managers
shows.
The Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply said its purchasing
managers' index rose from 51.2 per cent in February to 53.9 per cent last
month. The index, based on a weighted average of movements of several
components, including new orders, output and employment, was above the 50
per cent level that indicates expansion in the manufacturing economy for the
second consecutive month.
The output and order components of the index rose sharply in March and have
now indicated increasing levels of manufacturing activity and new orders
from home and abroad for five consecutive months. The output index rose to
58.6 per cent in last month from 53.8 per cent in February, while the
new-orders index advanced to 57.1 per cent from 53.9 per cent.
The institute, which says it represents UK purchasing managers with overall
spending power of Pounds 250bn a year, said many companies had reported an
improvement in foreign and domestic trade that exceeded normal seasonal
trends.
However, the recovery in industry's fortunes has yet to have a positive
impact on employment. The employment index increased slightly last month to
47.2 per cent from February's 46.1 per cent.
