<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Fears of forestry sell-off sparked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government was accused yesterday of planning to privatise the Forestry
Commission after Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, who is also responsible
for the commission, revealed that he had set up a committee 'to review
options for the ownership and management of Forestry Commission woodlands'.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's shadow environmental protection secretary, said
privatisation of the commission's woodland would mean less public access and
diminish the drive for conservation.
Mr Lang said in a Commons written answer that a committee of officials from
the Treasury, Ministry of Agriculture, Welsh Office and the Environment
Department under the chairmanship of the Scottish Office was also reviewing
the effectiveness of forestry investment incentives.
The commission is the biggest landowner in Britain, possessing 1.14m
hectares or 5 per cent of the land area of the UK.
</TEXT>
