<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Drivers in capital face road pricing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRIVERS could be charged for driving in London on a pay-as-you-go basis by
the end of the decade, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said
yesterday.
The aim would be to tackle congestion by making people think twice before
taking cars on the roads at busy times.
The most likely system would require drivers to fit in their cars, at their
own expense, electronic meters which would clock up charges by communicating
with roadside beacons. Drivers would pay by inserting rechargeable 'smart
cards' into their meters at the start of each journey and the meters would
deduct payments as journeys progressed.
The controversial plans emerged as the Department of Transport published the
results of a study of road pricing technology by the University of Newcastle
upon Tyne.
Mr MacGregor said: 'We have to consider new ways of preventing road
congestion in London from getting worse as car ownership grows. Charging
drivers for using the capital's crowded roads is one possible solution.'
No decisions would be taken until a three-year transport department
investigation into the options for in London is concluded next year.
The report says that although there is not yet a suitable road-pricing
system, the technology is moving fast and the political obstacles are likely
to prove greater than the technological ones.
The Automobile Association said yesterday that motorists were already paying
for roads through taxation, and additional charges could not be justified:
'The key to solving London's traffic problems is to invest in public
transport.'
</TEXT>
