<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / London Ambulance board dissolved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE London Ambulance Service board was dissolved yesterday after a
devastatingly critical report on the failure of the capital's computerised
ambulance control system.
Under arrangements approved by Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary,
South West Thames regional health authority will oversee the service -
contrary to the trend towards devolved management in the National Health
Service.
Mrs Bottomley said yesterday that previous accountability arrangements had
left the ambulance service, board and health authority 'unclear about their
respective roles and responsibilities'.
Last month's report highlighted a series of management failures in the
London Ambulance Service, the biggest in the world, culminating in chaos
when the computer system collapsed.
It said the board had failed to seek or obtain enough information to
exercise its responsibilities and Mrs Bottomley gave the regional health
authority a month to produce a better structure.
As yesterday's changes were announced, evidence emerged that the service's
reputation for unreliability may have begun to cost it contracts in the
National Health Service market.
It has lost the contract to provide non-emergency hospital transport
services in Newham, east London and to Essex Ambulance Service. Other
contracts may be at risk.
Mr Martin Gorham, London Ambulance Service chief executive, said no
purchasing authority considering withdrawing contracts had said explicitly
it was because of concerns over the quality of performance, but he accepted
that 'an issue in determining contracts must be performance'.
South West Thames will set up a committee of the authority to oversee the
ambulance service.
It will also establish an advisory group of specialists in information
technology, accident and emergency medicine, industrial relations, finance
and marketing.
The authority plans other mechanisms to increase scrutiny and 'provide
safety valves in case of any failure in line management'.
These will include an annual report concentrating on performance;
performance reports to MPs, community health councils and local authorities,
and regular meetings between senior managers and full-time union officers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
