<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Chemical industry spending falls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL spending by the chemical industry, which usually accounts for a
sixth of UK manufacturing capital expenditure, fell 11 per cent last year to
Pounds 2.176bn. Spending is expected to fall a further 10 per cent this year
to Pounds 2bn, a Chemical Industries Association survey of 65 companies
shows.
The survey concludes that in spite of the emergence of some 'green shoots'
the outlook for 1993 is another tough year, with only a slow recovery for
the industry.
There will be no early reversal of the industry's downward trend in
investment spending, says the report. Capital expenditure is expected to
rise to Pounds 2.4bn next year, but fall back to Pounds 2.15bn the following
year.
The south-east and East Anglia will receive the largest share of investment
 -35 per cent - over the next three years, the north-west and Midlands will
receive 29 per cent, the north-east and Humberside 21 per cent and the
south-west 3 per cent. Wales will gain 3 per cent and Scotland 9 per cent.
This high investment in the south-east reflects the predominance of spending
by the pharmaceuticals industry - highly concentrated in the region.
About 43 per cent of investment over the next three years will be for
pharmaceuticals, 25 per cent for specialities, 23 per cent petrochemicals
and plastics, 7 per cent basic organics and fertilisers and 5 per cent
dyestuffs and pigments. Two years ago petrochemicals and plastics was the
largest sector, accounting for nearly 40 per cent of the total.
The proportion of spending on the environment increased from 14 per cent of
the total last year to 23 per cent by 1995. Over the next three years
environmentally-related capital spending is estimated at Pounds 1.18bn, in
real terms 22 per cent higher than in 1992.
The proportion of that spending attributable to legislative requirements
increases from 53 per cent in 1992 to 64 per cent in 1995. The association
says UK companies have lost business to overseas competitors because of lack
of clarity in procedures and administrative delays for the recently
introduced integrated pollution control. It said there was a threat of
further loss to countries where environmental and waste handling procedures
were less onerous.
The UK's 10 per cent fall in capital expenditure this year compares with
falls of 7.5 per cent in Germany, 10 per cent in Italy, 8 per cent in
Belgium, 6.5 per cent in the Netherlands, and 5 per cent in Spain.
Investment intentions survey, 1993. Chemical Industries Association. 071 834
3399
</TEXT>
