<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Rail strike to go ahead at midnight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAIL travellers were warned yesterday by British Rail to finish their
journeys by 10 o'clock tonight or risk being stranded.
Last-minute talks between BR management and union negotiators failed to
avert a 24-hour national rail strike which is due to start at midnight.
Members of the Rail, Maritime and Transport union are protesting about
threatened compulsory redundancies and the use of outside contractors.
Mr Paul Watkinson, BR group personnel director, said after the talks: 'They
asked me to give a guarantee of jobs for life in the railway which I
obviously couldn't give. They're asking for something no employee in the
land has got.'
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said the union regretted BR 'were
unable to see their way to meet what we thought were reasonable demands'.
In London, many buses will be off the roads in a separate dispute over cuts
in pay for employees.
Mr Steven Norris, London transport minister, last night warned commuters
that parking restrictions would be 'vigorously enforced' along main routes,
and announced a string of measures to cope with the expected influx of cars
during the rail strike.
</TEXT>
