<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / BAe says it needs airfield approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE has given way over its controversial plans to develop its
airfield at Filton, north Bristol, as a commercial airport and conceded it
should seek planning permission for change of use.
A fledgling airline, Air Bristol, had hoped to fly scheduled services from
Filton to European cities from late spring. Yesterday's agreement with
Northavon district council, which disputed BAe's claim not to need consent,
will mean a delay of several months even if the company's application is
successful. It could be much longer if the scheme goes to a public inquiry.
BAe, by claiming it did not need fresh planning consent, antagonised many
residents in the area, where more than 4,000 homes have been built in the
last few years in the new town of Bradley Stoke.
MANCHESTER Airport yesterday picked the site for its second runway, opting
for a line parallel and to the south of its existing runway, but beginning
half-way along and intruding into the Cheshire green belt. The runway would
enable the airport to expand to 30m passengers a year from its present level
of about 13m.
