<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Newspaper's free flights offer probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Advertising Standards Authority has begun an investigation into the
Sunday Times's offer of free air miles to its readers after receiving
complaints alleging that the terms of the promotion were misleading and
contained unreasonable restrictions.
The authority said it had received 21 complaints from the public about two
Sunday Times schemes since they were launched on February 21. That compares
with only 14 complaints about Hoover's much-criticised offer of free flights
to purchasers of its domestic appliances.
The Sunday Times campaign promises '500 instant air miles for every reader'.
Under one scheme readers are invited to collect vouchers worth 500 miles
every week over a three-month period and send them in for redemption.
The authority said readers had complained that the Sunday Times did not make
sufficiently clear that the air miles concerned could be used only towards
the purchase of tickets to destinations specified by the newspaper.
Among the destinations were Jeddah, Tehran and Abu Dhabi, which readers had
pointed out were unlikely choices for a holiday. Though some more popular
destinations, such as Melbourne and Hong Kong, were also included, the
authority said it could be difficult to collect enough air miles to cover
the full fares in the three months allowed.
The authority said it had also received complaints about a second scheme,
under which readers collect weekly vouchers worth 10 air miles which they
can use to buy a ticket to a destination of their choice.
The authority said it was investigating whether the Sunday Times had made
sufficiently clear that the offer was valid only if all the vouchers were
collected over a 12-month period and put in special booklets.
The Sunday Times confirmed that it had received a letter from the authority
about its investigation, but had no comment until the outcome was known. The
newspaper said it had received 'a handful' of complaints about the schemes.
The investigation is being made under a voluntary code on sales promotions
set up by the advertising industry.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
