<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / London drivers may face road pricing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDONERS could be charged for driving in the capital on a pay-as-you-go
basis by the end of the decade, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said
yesterday.
The aim would be to tackle congestion by making people think twice before
taking cars on the roads at busy times.
The most likely system would require drivers to fit their cars with
electronic meters at their own expense. The meters would clock up charges by
communicating with roadside beacons.
Drivers would pay by inserting rechargeable 'smart cards' into their meters
at the beginning of each journey and the meters would deduct payments from
the cards as journeys progressed.
Drivers penetrating the charging zone without a functioning meter, or an
equivalent device for visitors, would have their licence plates photographed
and face punishment.
The controversial plans emerged as the Department of Transport published the
results of a study of road pricing technology by the University of Newcastle
upon Tyne.
Mr MacGregor said: 'We have to consider new ways of preventing road
congestion in London from getting worse as car ownership grows. Charging
drivers for using the capital's crowded roads is one possible solution.'
No decisions would be taken until a three-year investigation into the
options for road pricing in London had been concluded by the Department of
Transport next year.
The report says that although there is not yet a suitable road pricing
system for the capital, the technology is moving fast. It concludes the
political obstacles are likely to prove greater than the technological ones.
A Review of Technology for Road Use Pricing in London. Department of
Transport, London Assessment Division, Room C14/10a, 2 Marsham Street,
London SW1P 3EB.
</TEXT>
