<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / World Trade News: R-R goes on attack over air subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROLLS-ROYCE, the UK aero-engine group, yesterday called for the extension of
last year's EC-US agreement on civil aircraft subsidies to cover aircraft
engines.
His call coincided with the start of talks in Brussels yesterday between US
and EC trade negotiators to review their recent agreement.
Sir Ralph Robins, the Rolls-Royce chairman, claimed that US aero-engine
manufacturers received more than Dollars 700m (Pounds 492m) a year in
financial support from the US government. Rolls-Royce received just Pounds
15m a year for research from the UK Department of Trade and Industry and the
Ministry of Defence, he said.
'There is no doubt that the level of US government support to its industry
makes life very difficult for us,' Sir Ralph told a House of Commons
committee reviewing the UK aerospace industry.
Rolls Royce had received Pounds 494.2m in UK government launch aid for civil
aircraft programmes since 1972, he said, but it was repaying about Pounds
30m a year to the Treasury. Between now and 2001, the company is expected to
repay nearly Pounds 500m to government.
The turmoil in the civil aviation industry has revived transatlantic trade
tensions over direct government support for the European Airbus programme.
But the EC has in turn accused the US of continuing to support its civil
aerospace industry with indirect subsidies through state agencies.
The dispute has focused on the airframe industry.
Rolls-Royce is now seeking to extend the agreement to cover engines. It said
civil aircraft engines had so far been excluded from the pact because of
opposition from General Electric and Pratt &amp; Whitney of the US.
Sir Ralph urged the UK government to provide greater research and
development support for the UK aerospace industry, especially in the field
of advanced materials.
'A new family of materials is coming to revolutionise aviation and its first
application will be on engines.' Unless Rolls-Royce remained in the
forefront of new materials technology, it risked losing out, he warned.
</TEXT>
