<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / World Trade News: The gospel according to trade's agnostic -
The emerging views of US negotiator Kantor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICKEY Kantor, the US trade representative, does not like 'theological
debate'. Over two days of talks in Brussels with EC trade officials, he made
this repeatedly clear.
As others grope to discern a clear US trade policy, he insists instead that
the administration is 'pragmatic', 'realistic' and 'results-oriented'.
In Brussels he went further: 'We see a trade policy emerging that is more
active, anticipatory, inclusive and flexible - incorporating new concerns
about the environment, competition policy, international labour standards,
science and technology policy, enlarging the productive capabilities of
developing countries.'
He talked about 'mutuality of obligation and comparability of action'. In
negotiations with the EC, his starting premise was simple: the US is one of
the most open markets in the world. The EC is by comparison closed. The US
task is to get other countries into line.
When asked if the trade policies of President Bill Clinton will be different
from those of his predecessors, Mr Kantor chose 'to reframe the question':
'Can we afford to have continuity for continuity's sake? Can we afford to
remain at a standstill, to live with old assumptions in the face of massive
and inexorable change in the new global economic environment?'
In the wake of these explanations, one Brussels-based trade analyst
commented: 'If Mr Kantor is averse to theological debate, he seems perfectly
happy to deal in metaphysics.'
In certain respects, it remains premature for Mr Kantor to talk more
clearly. The review of US trade policy demanded by Mr Clinton is still
incomplete. The president has still to confirm many of his trade
representatives. Many of those named are new to the area of trade.
Serious negotiation of issues involved with the Uruguay Round of world trade
talks remains impossible because Mr Clinton has yet to put to Congress
proposals renewing 'fast track' laws that would enable the administration to
present a 'take-it-or-leave-it' package.
So far, there are few results by which to measure US policy. Clashes between
the US and the EC over steel dumping, and Airbus subsidies were inherited
from the Bush administration.
'Get tough' threats in a row over EC procurement policy have yet to move
beyond bluff and brinkmanship. Deadlines for US sanctions have come and
gone. A meeting in Washington on April 19-20 is now set as a make-or-break
session, during which there will either be a settlement, or both sides will
be 'free to act as we wish'.
EC officials fear a crisis has been delayed rather than averted. They say
they would be prepared to bow to US demands to dismantle Article 29 of the
new Utilities directive, which discriminates in favour of EC bidders for
procurement contracts, but want the US in return to tackle its 'Buy America'
laws.
Throughout negotiations in Brussels on government procurement, Mr Kantor
neither bowed to, nor agreed to recognise, EC complaints that the 'Buy
America' act in the US strongly discriminates against foreign bidders for
contracts, in particular at a state and municipal level.
On Monday, Mr Kantor said categorically that the act 'has had no effect on
European suppliers'. His claim was embarrassingly contradicted by US
officials at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) in Geneva,
who at the very time he was speaking were vetoing for the second time a Gatt
panel ruling against the US for having barred a German company from a US
procurement contract through use of the law.
Trade experts also query Mr Clinton's commitment to multilateral trade rules
and 'honest-broker' settlement of trade disputes in the Gatt. In talks with
Mexico on the North American Free Trade Agreement, with the EC on Airbus,
steel, or procurement, or with Japan on semi-conductors, the US has shown a
clear preference for bilateral settlement of disputes.
President Clinton has also openly supported reinstatement of 'Super 301'
laws, which will entitle the US to target countries it sees as trading
unfairly, and impose sanctions if they do not change their ways.
The US has clearly targeted Japan as an unfair trader, with whom bilateral
negotiations offer the only route to opening the market. In Brussels, Mr
Kantor said the Uruguay Round would not be completed 'if Japan continues to
behave as if it had little stake in the outcome.'
The comment stirred a storm among Japanese trade officials. In Brussels, the
Japanese embassy said Mr Kantor 'had a misperception': 'Maybe he is not yet
fully familiar with the details of the realities.'
That Mr Kantor is new to his task is undeniable. But he is not new to the
domestic economic priorities that lie at the heart of the new president's
decision-making. What the Japanese may be seeing is evidence of new
priorities, in which the details of past realities count for much less.
One UK-based trade analyst commented: 'The US knows what it wants - it's
just not what other people think it should want.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
