<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Budget package close to being passed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton's budget package headed yesterday for final passage
after the House and the Senate agreed to reconcile their different versions
of the bill.
This paved the way for voting on the broad framework of Mr Clinton's budget
proposals before Congress breaks up this weekend for the Easter recess.
However, some members of Congress said the budget could unravel in the
summer when a more detailed bill will be drawn up, because of President
Clinton's controversial decision to remove a provision to end government
subsidies to ranchers and mining companies in the West.
This followed pressure on the White House by western senators who lobbied
against a planned increase in fees for the exploitation of federal lands in
the west to something approaching market levels.
The plan would have raised fees charged to ranchers who graze their cattle
on federal lands, and charged royalties from companies for minerals
extracted from government lands.
Administration officials say the fees and royalties will still be imposed in
a separate initiative, but some congressmen were furious at the climbdown,
and said the move would encourage other lobbyists to pick away at the bill.
'This is a fundamental mistake by the administration,' said Congressman
George Miller, chairman of the House of Representatives Natural Resources
committee.
Congressional aides say the climbdown contradicts Mr Clinton's plea to
members of congress to take his plan as a whole.
The detailed budget reconciliation bill, which will flesh out the budget
resolution bill, in the summer, was always expected to be a hard fight, as
Congress's enthusiasm for deficit reduction came face to face with the
realities of cutting individual, favourite programmes.
The success of the western senators may mean members are less willing to
submerge their local concerns.
</TEXT>
