<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Jamaica re-elects Patterson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAMAICA'S People's National party has been returned to power in a landslide
election victory which will also see Mr P J Patterson resume the premiership
he took over from Mr Michael Manley last year.
Mr Patterson, a 58-year-old lawyer, said the government would continue with
economic reforms which include the floating of the island's currency and the
sale of state enterprises.
Provisional results yesterday from Tuesday's poll gave the PNP 50 of the 60
seats contested, with five going to the opposition Jamaica Labour party led
by Mr Edward Seaga, a former prime minister. Five seats were still to be
declared.
The PNP's margin of victory was larger than expected and surprised even
party officials. A split in the JLP leadership is being partly blamed for
the party's poor showing and there were indications yesterday that Mr Seaga
might stand down.
