<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / MP uproar over guilty verdict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Indian parliament was in uproar yesterday over a court verdict in which
Mr Sharad Pawar, the chief minister of Maharashtra state and a potential
future prime minister, was found guilty of corrupt electoral practices,
writes Stefan Wagstyl.
Opposition members of both the upper and lower houses demanded Mr Pawar's
resignation and staged walk-outs in response to the ruling Congress (I)
party's refusal to allow a debate on the judgment on Tuesday by the Bombay
High Court.
Mr Pawar, who comes from Bombay, recently returned to the city as chief
minister of Maharashtra after serving as defence minister. He has taken
charge of efforts to rebuild confidence in Bombay following recent
inter-religious riots and terrorist bombings.
The judgment concerned a contest held in the parliamentary constituency of
South Ahmdnagar in Maharashtra during the 1991 general election.
The election was won by a Congress (I) party candidate strongly supported by
Mr Pawar.
But Mr Balasaheb Vikhe-Patil, the losing candidate from the left-wing Janata
Dal party, appealed against the poll result, alleging malpractice. The court
upheld his appeal, finding that Mr Pawar and the successful Congress (I)
candidate had defamed Mr Vikhe-Patil by wrongly alleging in speeches that he
had tried to bribe voters with money, gifts and alcohol.
Congress (I) is likely to appeal to the Supreme Court. If the appeal fails,
the election result will be set aside and a new poll held.
</TEXT>
