<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Farmers reap benefit of Indian reform: Agricultural exports
will be encouraged as New Delhi slackens reins on sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIAN farmers are to be encouraged to export mainstream agricultural
products, in the most significant liberalisation of the country's farm trade
policy since independence.
The policy, announced yesterday, will extend to farmers the wide-ranging
economic reform programme launched in mid-1991 by Mr P V Narasimha Rao, the
prime minister.
The reforms will undermine a central element of post-independence
agricultural policy - the principle of restraining exports to keep down
domestic food prices and reduce the risk of famine. The measures acknowledge
that the old system, with its panoply of price controls and subsidies, has
contributed to the stagnation of agriculture in many districts and deprived
India of a potentially huge source of export earnings.
Mr Pranab Mukherjee, the commerce minister, said in a statement that
promoting agricultural exports was essential for boosting investment in
agriculture, raising incomes in rural areas and ensuring that the benefits
of export-led growth reached the country as a whole. The government is
concerned that export growth has flagged recently. However, it risks
political opposition over the changes since the reforms might lead to higher
domestic food prices.
Much will depend on the extent to which the government continues to pay out
food price subsidies. There might also be friction in rural areas between
rich farmers, who can afford to invest to take advantage of export
opportunities, and poorer ones.
Under past policies, agricultural exports have been dominated by
internationally traded commodity crops including tea, coffee, high-grade
rice, nuts and spices. Exports of staple crops have either been restricted
or banned outright.
Fruits and vegetables accounted for just Dollars 142m (Pounds 100m) of total
agricultural exports of Dollars 3.3bn in the year to March 1992. Processed
foods totalled only Dollars 77m.
Under the new policy, businessmen will be free to set up export-oriented
units in agriculture, horticulture, animal husbandry, poultry, and
fish-farming. They will be allowed to import capital equipment and materials
duty free - in the same way that industrial export-oriented units already
can.
In an extra concession, such units will be allowed to sell up to 50 per cent
of their output in the domestic market, compared with a 25 per cent limit
for industry.
The immediate impact on exports will be slight as such units could take time
to establish themselves. But the potential effects are great since fertile
parts of India, such as the northern state of Punjab, could well become
internationally competitive exporters.
In other measures announced yesterday, the government permitted accountants,
lawyers, journalists and other professionals to import capital equipment at
a concessional duty rate of 15 per cent.
Mr Mukherjee said in his statement that India's 'abundance of highly skilled
human resources' gave it a competitive advantage in services.
The minister also took a further 144 items off the list of banned imports.
The newly decontrolled products include poultry feed and other goods of
interest to farmers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
