<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Japan's banks sell Y682bn of bad loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING Japanese banks said yesterday they had sold Y681.7bn (Pounds 3.9bn)
of their bad property loans in recent weeks to a new agency, which purchased
them at a generous 66 per cent of face value.
At the same time the leading 21 banks are believed to have successfully
hurdled the 8 per cent target set for capital adequacy ratios for the fiscal
year which ended yesterday. About eight of the largest 11 commercial banks
are believed to have capital to assets ratios at a comfortable 9 per cent.
The loan purchases, announced through the Bank of Japan, were by the
Co-operative Credit Purchasing Company, an industry body established earlier
this year to try to clear away the large pile of non-performing
property-related loans.
Banks bring their bad loans to the CCPC, which values the property and other
collateral and buys the loan credit, allowing insititutions to write off the
difference, at a favourable tax rate. It is hoped the company will help to
put a floor under property prices through its valuations.
The CCPC said that the loan credits bought in recent weeks came from 35
banks and life assurers. The banks have to provide the money for the CCPC to
buy the loans, and remain responsible for selling the property, even though
they have theoretically sold the collateral to the company.
Before the CCPC began valuing the collateral there were concerns that the
property valuations could be overly generous, undermining the potential role
as a guide to prospective land pruchasers. The 66 per cent figure suggests
that banks either brought in their most attractive bad loans or that the
valuations were generous.
The leading 21 banks were officially estimated to have non-performing loans
of Y12,300bn at the end of last September. But that figure is regarded as an
underestimate as it does not include affiliates' bad loans or the increasing
amount of loans on which token repayments are made to ensure they are not
officially 'bad'.
But the banks will be relieved that their capital adequacy ratios, as
defined by the Bank for International Settlements, are relatively healthy.
They have been helped by the surge in Tokyo stock prices in recent weeks,
and the strengthening yen.
</TEXT>
