<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Nato jets authorised to down intruders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at the UN and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council last night gave the go-ahead for Nato warplanes to
patrol Bosnian air space and shoot down any military aircraft violating the
'no-fly' ban.
A resolution, delayed by Russian doubts, authorised enforcement of the
no-fly zone by 14-0, with China abstaining.
The vote came as pressure mounted on the Bosnian Serbs to join the Moslems
and Croatians in signing the peace settlement drawn up by the international
mediators, Lord Owen and Mr Cyrus Vance, dividing Bosnia into 10
semi-autonomous provinces.
Russia has been concerned to limit the way the no-fly zone is enforced. It
is prepared to sanction shooting down any Serb aircraft violating Bosnian
air space but not attacks on aircraft on the ground.
Mr Yuli Vorontsov, Russia's Security Council representative, stressed the
need to co-ordinate combat operations with the UN in New York.
He reminded Bosnian Serbs if they accepted the Vance-Owen plan the UN
resolution would not have to be implemented. In any event, it will not go
into effect for 14 days.
China's delegate objected to invoking mandatory enforcement provisions of
Chapter VII of the UN Charter and also cited reservations voiced by the UN
field commander.
The Security Council is expected to vote later this week to endorse the
Vance-Owen plan and tighten economic sanctions against Serbia. The US and EC
appeared to have resolved differences over endorsement of the plan, about
which the Clinton administration has had reservations.
Earlier, Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader, told Mr John Major, UK
prime minister, in a letter 'we are now two-thirds of the way to peace'. He
urged Mr Major to support changes in the map of the proposed provinces.
</TEXT>
