<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Balladur gives his team pro-EC stamp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE make-up of his cabinet and his first directions to it yesterday suggest
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur is falling in with President Mitterrand's
wishes for a government which shows itself pro-European abroad and concerned
with social issues at home.
The new government's programme will not become clear until Mr Balladur
outlines it to parliament next Thursday. But already, after an informal
meeting with his new team yesterday, Mr Balladur made it known that his
first foreign trip would be to see Chancellor Helmut Kohl after Easter, and
that his new ministers should get cracking on pruning this year's yawning
budget deficit, reducing the level of unemployment that now stands at 3m,
and saving the state pension and welfare systems from bankruptcy.
The key pointer to Mr Balladur's desire for pro-EC government, with its
centre of gravity lying in the moderate centre-right part of the political
spectrum, was his determination to bring Mrs Simone Veil back to domestic
politics. He had no 'party political' reason to do so. Mrs Veil last held
office in France in 1979, when she resigned to become the first president of
the directly-elected European Parliament where she has been since. She
played no real part in the recent election campaign, is a centrist, but no
longer has any close ties to Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing's Union for French
Democracy (UDF) party.
Yet, she has been made the senior of four 'ministers of state' who rank
above ordinary ministers. In protocol terms, this makes her Mr Balladur's
deputy, with a weight beyond her actual responsibility for social, health
and urban affairs. Mr Balladur wanted Mrs Veil, to whom he first offered the
justice ministry, in his team because this 65-year-old Jewish survivor of a
German concentration camp symbolises a rare kind of tough morality in French
politics.
As the author of France's 1974 abortion law, and a dedicated European, she
gives the government both a progressive and a pro-EC flavour for the price
of just one post in a cabinet which Mr Balladur wanted to restrict in
number. If the government were to be pushed off its pro-EC rails, Mrs Veil
would be the first to pull the alarm cord. Mr Balladur, himself the first of
Europe's finance ministers to propose in 1987 setting up a European central
bank, may think that no bad thing.
There are other reasons why the composition of France's new government will
give no comfort to anti-Maastricht Conservatives in Britain, or discomfort
to governments of the 10 countries that have ratified the European union
treaty. The Balladur team contains only two anti-Maastricht ministers - Mr
Charles Pasqua and Mr Francois Fillon - but they are safely parked at the
interior and research ministries, respectively. The maverick Mr Alain
Madelin has free market doubts about fixed exchange rates, but he will have
his hands full setting up the new ministry for small business.
Mainstream responsibility for European policy will fall on other shoulders.
Mr Edmond Alphandery is effectively the country's new finance minister, but
nominally only responsible for the 'economy', with the word 'finance'
excised from his title. This reflects the determination of Mr Balladur,
himself a former finance minister, to exercise a strong role on monetary
policy. A clash is possible. Quite quickly, Mr Alphandery can be expected to
assert himself, particularly on the urgent matter of making the Bank of
France autonomous, an issue on which Mr Alphandery has strong views.
For the moment all the government has on paper about the change in the
central bank's status is a draft statute.
Mr Alain Juppe's appointment as foreign minister gives him a chance to come
out from the long shadow of Mr Jacques Chirac, the neo-Gaullist Republican
Rally (RPR) leader., The odds are that Mr Juppe will take it, and prove
himself more pro-European than his patron.
However, less able to resist the influence of Mr Chirac, who has stayed out
of the government to run for the presidency on a populist, not to say,
protectionist platform, may be the new farm minister, Mr Jean Puech. He is
ostensibly pro-Maastricht, but may well be unable to resist pressure from
the farmers, probably egged on by Mr Chirac, for a confrontation with
Brussels. Mr Puech was not Mr Balladur's first choice. Another UDF centrist,
Mr Charles Millon, refused it three times, saying it would be incompatible
with his pro-EC convictions. Clearly Mr Millon smelt coming trouble.
GOVERNMENT TEAM: Prime Minister Edouard Balladur presenting his new cabinet
in Paris yesterday. Alain Juppe (foreign affairs), Pierre Mehaignerie
(justice), Simone Veil (social affairs), Balladur, Charles Pasqua
(interior), Francois Leotard (defence). Jean Puech (agriculture), Jacques
Toubon (culture), Alain Madelin (trade), Bernard Bosson (transport), Michel
Giraud (labour), Nicolas Sarkozy (budget, government spokesman). Philippe
Douste-Blazy (health), Philippe Mestre (veterans affairs), Alain Carignon
(communications), Michele Alliot-Marie (sports), Lucette Michaux-Chevry
(humanitarian affairs). Daniel Hoeffel (territorial management), Pascal
Clement (parliamentary relations), Michel Roussin (co-operation), Alain
Lamassoure (Europe). Edmond Alphandery (finance), Gerard Longuet (industry),
Francois Bayrou (education) and Michel Barnier (environment)
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
