<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Security council split on sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISAGREEMENTS between permanent members of the United Nations Security
Council are likely to delay further the adoption of a draft resolution for
tougher sanctions against Serbia - already postponed three times last week.
Both the US and Russia have reservations about different aspects of the
resolution which no one now expects to be adopted before President Clinton
and President Yeltsin meet this weekend.
Russia has said it would vote against the enforcement of a no-fly zone over
Bosnia unless the resolution was modified to exclude attacks on ground
targets, the Russian Interfax news agency reported.
The harder Russian position follows demands by conservative
parliamentarians, who criticise Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the liberal foreign
minister, for co-operating with western governments in condemning Serb
military action in Bosnia. Russian conservatives have been upset that Moscow
appeared to be abandoning its traditional Serbian allies.
Meanwhile, to the surprise of European members of the Security Council, the
US has objected to including a clear endorsement of the international peace
plan for Bosnia, drawn up by Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen, as part of the
new sanctions resolution.
The draft resolution, backed by Britain, France and Spain, is intended to
persuade Belgrade to put pressure on the Bosnian Serbs to sign the peace
plan, which has so far been endorsed only by the Bosnian Croats and Moslems.
According to some reports, the US remains divided about the workability of
the plan and has doubts about its fairness to the Moslems.
</TEXT>
