<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / W German industrial output may fall 7%: Construction is only
growing sector, says Ifo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD and DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEST GERMANY'S industrial production could decline by as much as 7 per cent
this year, Ifo, the Munich-based economics institute, reported in a monthly
survey of manufacturers, distributors and building companies.
The report says that plans to reduce investment sharply and cut production
were the principal causes for the expected decline.
Producers sampled by Ifo said they would continue to reduce output, leaving
utilisation of industrial capacity at 80.4 per cent by the end of the year
compared with 85 per cent in the middle of 1992.
The most pronounced fall will be in the motor industry, with output dropping
by 'nearly 20 per cent'. Exports will continue to be negatively affected by
the strong D-Mark and high production costs, the report says.
Production of lorries and delivery vans could also sink, by 14 per cent this
year compared with 6.5 per cent in 1992. Engineering products are set to
fall by 8 per cent in 1993. The chemical sector is also expected to reduce
production by 4 to 5 per cent this year, the report notes.
The textile industry plans to decrease output by 8 per cent while the
clothing industry is expected to fair relatively better than last year, with
production falling by 5 per cent against 12 per cent in 1992.
Only the construction industry will continue to record growth, the report
says. But output for 1993 will grow only 1 per cent, compared with 5.6 per
cent last year. The report blamed the general economic decline for such
lower results. In east Germany, the construction industry will continue to
grow strongly, with output expected to increase by 20 per cent this year.
Meanwhile, Mr Ulrich Cartellieri, board director of Deutsche Bank
responsible for macro-economics, said yesterday that the 'solidarity pact'
recently concluded for the east German economy was only the first step
towards big structural changes in the German economy.
He said the government should tackle three issues as a matter of great
urgency:
It should make 'substantial, rather than marginal' cuts in budget spending
to release funds for investment in eastern Germany;
It should take steps to privatise industry as a way of reducing the DM400bn
(Pounds 169.4bn) debts inherited from the former East Germany. 'Reduction of
these debts. . . is inconceivable without the mobilisation of public sector
assets,' he said.
It should take steps to eliminate the causes of excessive borrowing.
Deutsche Bank results, Page 28
</TEXT>
