<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Amato asked to stay at helm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro has asked the Amato government to
stay on in office - at least until the referendums due on April 18 - in the
absence of early agreement on an alternative.
This is the upshot of an exhaustive series of consultations held throughout
Tuesday by President Scalfaro. The main parties, while unanimous in calling
for a government based on broader support than the current four-party
coalition, are deadlocked on how this should be achieved.
The lira, under strong pressure since the beginning of the week because of
political uncertainties, recovered slightly yesterday. But this appeared to
reflect the market's view that the currency was undervalued at close to
L1,000 to the D-Mark rather than confidence in a satisfactory political
solution.
Mr Giuliano Amato, the Socialist prime minister, is now in the hapless
position of being obliged to soldier on, heading a government whose days are
numbered. One of the main stumbling blocks to finding a broader based
government is the reluctance of the former communist Party of the Democratic
Left (PDS) and the Republicans to join forces, albeit for a limited period,
with the ruling parties whom they regard as discredited.
The impermanence of the government was underlined yesterday by Mr Amato's
decision not to fill the finance ministry portfolio. This was left vacant on
Tuesday by the resignation of Mr Franco Reviglio, a Socialist senator,
because of his alleged involvement in the corruption scandals. When Mr
Gianni Fontana resigned as minister of agriculture on March 21 for the same
reason, Mr Amato replaced him to show his determination to keep the
government alive.
Mr Reviglio, the fifth minister to resign because of the corruption
investigations, is alleged to have received illicit funds while chairman of
Eni, the state oil concern, from 1983 to 1989. The gap between what Italy's
political parties said they received in revenue and what they said they
spent quadrupled during 1992 to L27bn (Pounds 11.3m).
According to the parties' balance sheets published yesterday, just a week
after their 1991 accounts, revenues totalled L279.4bn while outgoings were
L306bn. The accumulated deficit of the parties reached L134bn, a 24 per cent
rise during the year. The accounts, prepared in the light of investigations
into illicit party funding, still fail to reflect the true picture.
</TEXT>
