<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / EC fears link to Italian scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONCERN is growing in Brussels that European Community institutions could be
dragged into Italy's spreading corruption scandals, following the suicide of
a senior EC official and the disappearance of a former official.
A senior Italian bureaucrat, formerly in charge of the Community's
tobacco-growing subsidy regime, jumped from a window of the offices of the
Agriculture Directorate in Brussels two days ago, only weeks ahead of an
internal Commission hearing about tobacco fraud. Mr Antonio Quatraro was
moved from his post two years ago after he was implicated by the EC's Court
of Auditors in fraud involving payments to Italian and Greek tobacco growers
and processors for 'phantom' crops.
The suicide comes just after the disappearance of a former senior official
at the European Parliament, and close aide to Mr Bettino Craxi, the Italian
Socialist leader being investigated on multiple charges of corruption in
Italy.
Mr Mauro Giallombardo, secretary general of the confederation of European
socialist parties until 1990 and then on contract as a senior official in
the Parliament secretariat general, dropped out of sight after being forced
to resign in February. The Italian judicial authorities have issued a
warrant for his arrest.
Belgium's authorities are understood to be investigating his possible links
to the Agusta affair, involving kickbacks paid on Belgium's 1988 purchase of
helicopters from the Italian company Agusta. Reports in Italy, Luxembourg
and Belgium allege that two subsidiaries of a company called Merchant
Italia, set up in Luxembourg by Mr Giallombardo, are being examined as
possible conduits for kickbacks.
The European Parliament is holding an inquiry into Mr Giallombardo's
activities, officials confirmed yesterday.
Mr Quatraro was an adviser on international aspects of the EC's common
agricultural policy.
Brussels police said yesterday they were satisfied it was suicide and were
not pursuing inquiries into his death.
There is no firm evidence to link Mr Quatraro with the series of Italian
corruption scandals. But Commission officials said yesterday they were
puzzled that the prospect of a disciplinary hearing should have prompted
suicide, when Mr Quatraro probably could have been quietly retired from the
Brussels executive without facing criminal charges.
Mr Giallombardo, after Italian Socialist pressure, was found a temporary
post in the Parliament's secretariat.
'We were totally unaware at the time of his transfer of the nature of the
activities he is now accused of,' a senior official in the secretariat
general said yesterday. Mr Giallombardo ceased appearing for work from July
1991, the official said. He finally accepted repeated invitations to resign
in January this year, after letters had been sent to his Luxembourg address.
Italy has a reputation for misusing EC funds, but not necessarily of getting
away with it.
The Rome government is due to repay the Community some Ecu2.3bn (Pounds
1.8bn) for illicitly exceeding the milk quota fixed under the Common
Agricultural Policy. Over Ecu3bn of regional funds earmarked for Italy are
being withheld because the European Commission is not satisfied with some of
the programmes Italy has put forward.
</TEXT>
