<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / House arrest for Fiat executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Francesco Mattioli, Fiat's chief financial officer, was yesterday allowed
to swap prison for house arrest after being held in Milan's San Vittore jail
since February 22 on charges of corruption and illicit financing of
political parties.
The charges against Mr Mattioli, one of the three most senior executives of
the Turin motor group, refer to illegal payments of L1.8bn (Pounds 750,000)
made during the construction of the Milan metro in which Fiat's construction
arm, Cogefar-Impresit, was involved.
Last week, a civil liberties tribunal refused to release Mr Mattioli from
prison on the grounds he could prejudice investigations by Milan
magistrates.
The court also disclosed allegations of illicit use of overseas accounts by
Fiat subsidiaries, including Cogefar Camerun, in Cameroon.
This decision provoked a furious reaction from Mr Cesare Romiti, Fiat's
chief executive, who claimed the courts had no idea how a multinational
operated.
But at least one newspaper speculated yesterday that Mr Mattioli had helped
the magistrates with their inquiries after an unexpected three-hour meeting
in San Vittore with Mr Antonio Di Pietro, one of the leading Milan
investigative magistrates.
Milan magistrates are understood to have presented Mr Mattioli with evidence
of funds being passed in 1992 through Banco Unione Commercio of Lugano, 100
per cent owned by Fiat, to accounts held in Switzerland respectively by the
chief treasurers of the Christian Democrat and Socialist parties.
Mr Severino Citaristi, who has resigned from his position in the Christian
Democrat party, has received over 20 notices of being under investigation on
various counts of illicit party funding. Mr Vincenzo Balzamo, his Socialist
opposite number, died last autummn of a heart atack after being told he was
under investigation.
Magistrates yesterday questioned Mr Roberto Araldi, a Milan accountant, over
alleged payments by Fiat Avio, the group's aerospace turbines subsidiary, to
board members of Enel, the state electricity authority, for a L400bn gas
turbine contract.
</TEXT>
