<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 93 / Bonn proposes new recycling measure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German cabinet yesterday approved a proposed environmental law which
will force industrial producers to ensure the collection and recycling of
waste consumer products.
The law, which will be presented to parliament this year, should come into
effect in about three years and will effectively transfer to the private
sector the costs of collecting and recycling waste now assumed by local
councils.
The Environment Ministry said: 'Our philosophy aims to make industry, and
not the state, pay for recycling consumer products.'
However, consumers may be the first to bear the cost of the recycling.
Industrialists, who have opposed the law fiercely, say it will force
companies to charge higher prices.
'It is time to understand that there simply is a price to be paid for
recycling,' Mr Klaus Topfer, environment minister said yesterday.
A similar law for consumer packaging, adopted two years ago, prompted
industrial producers to create a nationwide waste-collecting company, Duales
System Deutschland (DSD).
Consumers have been charged higher prices for products collected by DSD,
which bear a distinctive green dot.
Such a system may also be set up as a result of the new law, with producers
creating a special organisation in charge of collecting consumer products
and ensuring their recycling. Products sold in Germany by foreign companies
could also be collected.
The Environment Ministry hopes industry will ultimately be forced to
manufacture products which can be more easily recycled.
The new law will also restrict industry's opportunity to dump or incinerate
waste.
</TEXT>
